INSERT INTO `atividade_idioma` VALUES (2,55,'Atividade 1: Prática de escuta e repetição','<p><em>Agora, que tal escutar e repetir o di&aacute;logo? Use os bot&otilde;es para escutar a historinha que voc&ecirc; acabou de ver e gravar sua repeti&ccedil;&atilde;o. Depois, compare a sua grava&ccedil;&atilde;o com as falas dos personagens. Voc&ecirc; pode gravar e ouvir quantas vezes quiser.</em></p>\r\n'),(2,58,'Atividade 2: Soletração','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Saber soletrar sempre ajuda a resolver casos de d&uacute;vidas como essas. O alfabeto ingl&ecirc;s &eacute; formado por 26 letras, Nenhuma delas tem diacr&iacute;ticos (como o cedilha do </span>&ccedil;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"> portugu&ecirc;s, por exemplo). Vamos revis&aacute;-las?</span></em></p>\r\n'),(2,61,'Atividade 3: Título e sentido','<p><em>O t&iacute;tulo desta unidade &eacute; <strong>I see you</strong>. Ap&oacute;s ter conhecido a historinha com a Dra. Lima e os outros personagens e realizado as atividades anteriores, por que voc&ecirc; acha que a unidade tem esse t&iacute;tulo? Grave um arquivo de &aacute;udio com sua resposta. </em></p>\r\n'),(2,63,'Atividade 1: Escuta e repetição','<p>Escuta e repeti&ccedil;&atilde;o</p>\r\n'),(2,73,'Atividade 2: (Im)possibilidades Enunciativas','<p><em>Priscila:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m Priscila... I don&rsquo;t know this &lsquo;curse&rsquo;&hellip; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Professora:&nbsp;&nbsp; Oh, course not curse, ok?</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Priscila:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What? I said wrong?</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Professora: Yes, you said &lsquo;curse&rsquo; but the word is &lsquo;course&rsquo;. Curse is a completely different thing&hellip;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1) Como voc&ecirc; se sentiria no lugar de Priscila?&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2) Como voc&ecirc; entende o posicionamento da professora?​</strong></p>\r\n'),(2,74,'Atividade 3: O que é inteligibilidade? ','<p>Observe a fala de Priscila no Quadro 7 (<em>ok&hellip; right. I can&rsquo;t speak&hellip; I understand more and read... Well&hellip; this course about methodology?</em>). Apesar de se mostrar com algumas inconsist&ecirc;ncias gramaticais, pode-se compreend&ecirc;-la no contexto em que &eacute; enunciada. Isso nos remete &agrave; discuss&atilde;o sobre o conceito de <strong>inteligibilidade</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nesse &aacute;udio 1, a partir de uma situa&ccedil;&atilde;o relativamente simples, aponta para as rela&ccedil;&otilde;es de poder que constituem a tomada da palavra, fazendo com que esta jamais seja um ato neutro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ao dizer <em>I&rsquo;d like to know how we can have access to the texts </em>(&aacute;udio 2)<em>, </em>Juliana n&atilde;o est&aacute; interessada em uma mera informa&ccedil;&atilde;o. O que est&aacute; aqui em jogo, mais do que a referencialidade da linguagem, &eacute; a possibilidade, para os falantes, de produzirem certos dizeres e assumirem lugares (social, discursivo) perante o outro. Diante da sugest&atilde;o da professora para que os alunos adquirissem os livros a serem estudados na disciplina, Juliana se posiciona contrariando a expectativa da docente (<em>But do you know if they are available in the library? I guess they&rsquo;re a little bit expensive</em>) (&aacute;udio 3) e, confrontando, de certa forma, uma voz institucional.</p>\r\n'),(2,75,'Atividade 1: Escuta e repetição','<p>Escuta e repeti&ccedil;&atilde;o dos di&aacute;logos</p>\r\n'),(2,76,'Atividade 2: Expressões Idiomáticas','<p>Observe algumas express&otilde;es idiom&aacute;ticas que podem ser usadas para substituir as ditas pelos personagens.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Felicity: Good idea,&nbsp;<strong>I&rsquo;m starving</strong>!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I could eat a horse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I could murder a (burger /&nbsp;steak&nbsp;/ pizza) right now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so ravenous I could eat a horse!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">4)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so starved I could eat a horse!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">5)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m famished. I could murder a burger!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">6)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so hungry I could murder a whole pizza right now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ethan: Are you crazy? Oh God!&nbsp;<strong>You eat a lot</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have you ever gone bananas? You eat like a horse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have you ever gone bananas? You eat like a pig.</p>\r\n'),(2,77,'Atividade 3: Praticando os modais','<p>Escolha o melhor sentido para esses verbos modais.</p>\r\n'),(2,78,'Atividade 3: The food song','<p>Observe as figuras com comidas e coisas relacionadas &agrave; comida que se encontram na can&ccedil;&atilde;o: <strong>The Food Song</strong> de Barbra Lica.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(2,79,'Atividade 4: The food song (letra e vídeo)','<p>The Food Song<br />\r\nBy Barbra Lica</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nHey, I had a bad day,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And I wondered how it <strong>TASTES</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I ATE...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And then I served myself a second <strong>PLATE</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad week,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And I wonder if it&#39;s <strong>SWEET</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I&#39;ll <strong>EAT</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Cause I deserve to give myself a treat...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sadness tastes like <strong>FRENCH FRIES</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And anger tastes like <strong>WINE</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They&#39;re only <strong>GRAPES </strong>but give them time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad night,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I wrapped it up in <strong>PIE</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And let it <strong>BAKE</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So all my feelings taste like <strong>TENDERFLAKE</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh joy, my mum just called.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And she&#39;s appalled because my dad don&#39;t want to <strong>SPOON</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ll take that <strong>SPOON</strong>, and put some <strong>ICE-CREAM </strong>on my afternoon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But guilty tastes like <strong>NOODLES</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lonely tastes like <strong>BREAD</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But <strong>TOAST </strong>can make a royal friend, hmmm!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yup! Everything is wonderful...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yeah! So walk it off, walk it off,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Circle the block,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <strong>COOKIES </strong>and <strong>CREAM</strong> are starting to talk to me...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m just crazy...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But crazy tastes so good,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crazy tastes so nice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crazy tastes like never-have-to-go outside.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here we go now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day so I ate it all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED</strong>.</p>\r\n'),(2,80,'Atividade 5: The food song (Karaoke)','<p>Vamos cantar! Ou&ccedil;a e repita!</p>\r\n'),(2,81,'Atividade 7: Combinar as frases','<p>Combine a express&atilde;o idiom&aacute;tica com o seu significado.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Your eyes are bigger than your stomach</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Have you ever gone bananas?</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Compare apples to oranges</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Eat like a horse</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Cry over spilled milk</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Piece of cake</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Bring home the bacon</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Have egg on one&rsquo;s face</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) I ate like a pig</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) A rotten apple</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) A smart cookie</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) As busy as popcorn on a skillet</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Back to the salt mines</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Big cheese</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Bite the hand that feeds one</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) I&rsquo;m cheesed off</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Couch potato</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) As cool as a cucumber</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Fruits of one&rsquo;s labor</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Hot potato</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n'),(2,83,'Atividade 6: Leitura e compreensão do texto','<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">Leia e responda as quest&otilde;es!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Our Moods, Our Foods</strong></span><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:18px\">The messy relationship between how we feel and what we eat</span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"c-article-meta\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; -webkit-box-align: baseline; align-items: baseline; display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<address>\r\n<address><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><a class=\"c-byline__link\" href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/author/julie-beck/\" style=\"color: rgb(231, 19, 26); background-color: transparent; text-decoration-line: none; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit;\">JULIE BECK</a>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:10px\">MARCH 6, 2014</span></address>\r\n</address>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0)\">Eating a meal, any meal, reliably makes an animal, any animal, calmer and more lethargic. This means humans, too. Hunger makes animals alert and irritable, which explains why couples always fight about where to eat dinner. This emotional response encourages the animals to find food.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">But all this is only in the broadest, most primal &ldquo;eating = good, not eating = bad&rdquo; way. The details of the relationship between foods and moods end up being a little contradictory and a lot complicated.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">What we tend to think of as &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a specific kind of eating and a specific kind of emotion&mdash;eating sugary, fatty, carb-y, unhealthy foods as a coping mechanism for feeling upset. &nbsp;In reality, &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a much broader term.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We eat for a variety of different emotions and we eat in a variety of different circumstances which are in turn connected with emotions,&rdquo; Meryl Gardner, a marketing professor at the University of Delaware, says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner was the lead author on a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057740814000060\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">new study</a>&nbsp;published in the&nbsp;<em>Journal of Consumer Psychology,&nbsp;</em>which looked at food choice and mood, adding to a fairly extensive body of research that already exists on the interplay between moods and foods.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">There seems to be a clear, fairly consistent connection between negative emotions and unhealthy foods, though there are individual variations for what&nbsp;<em>kind</em>&nbsp;of snack people want. In a bad mood, people&rsquo;s hands tend to float to the cookie jar, the candy bag, the snack drawer. What&rsquo;s less clear is what foods we&rsquo;re drawn to in a positive mood.</span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">What we tend to think of as &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a specific kind of eating and a specific kind of emotion&mdash;eating sugary, fatty, carb-y, unhealthy foods as a coping mechanism for feeling upset. &nbsp;In reality, &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a much broader term.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We eat for a variety of different emotions and we eat in a variety of different circumstances which are in turn connected with emotions,&rdquo; Meryl Gardner, a marketing professor at the University of Delaware, says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner was the lead author on a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057740814000060\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">new study</a>&nbsp;published in the&nbsp;<em>Journal of Consumer Psychology,&nbsp;</em>which looked at food choice and mood, adding to a fairly extensive body of research that already exists on the interplay between moods and foods.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">There seems to be a clear, fairly consistent connection between negative emotions and unhealthy foods, though there are individual variations for what&nbsp;<em>kind</em>&nbsp;of snack people want. In a bad mood, people&rsquo;s hands tend to float to the cookie jar, the candy bag, the snack drawer. What&rsquo;s less clear is what foods we&rsquo;re drawn to in a positive mood.</span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Some studies say we still want treats. A&nbsp;<a href=\"http://psycnet.apa.org/?&amp;fa=main.doiLanding&amp;doi=10.1037/0021-843X.101.2.348\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">1992 study</a>&nbsp;and a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ac.els-cdn.com/S019566630290499X/1-s2.0-S019566630290499X-main.pdf?_tid=edbdeba6-a479-11e3-a8a5-00000aacb360&amp;acdnat=1394033113_c88ed7a56c3e1767060124c3588f4ec2\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">2002 study</a>&nbsp;(one on women, one on men) found that joy led to increased consumption of indulgent foods. A 2013 study in&nbsp;<em>Appetite</em>&nbsp;titled &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S019566631300130X\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">Happy Eating: The underestimated role of overeating in a positive mood</a>&rdquo; points out the potential for increased consumption (in this case of chips and chocolate) when we&rsquo;re feeling good.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Other research says just the opposite&mdash;that we&rsquo;re more likely to eschew the sugar/carb rush when happy. In 2010,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.1086/655665?uid=3739256&amp;uid=2&amp;uid=4&amp;sid=21103592979347\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">researchers found</a>&nbsp;that people in a positive mood were more likely to choose grapes over chocolate than those in a neutral mood.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.1086/597159?uid=3739256&amp;uid=2&amp;uid=4&amp;sid=21103592979347\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">Another study</a>&nbsp;offers a qualification, finding that people would choose healthy foods if they felt like their good mood was going to stick around; if not, they might eat more indulgent foods, to keep the good vibes going.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner&rsquo;s study also found a connection between negative moods and unhealthy foods, and positive moods and healthy foods, but she and her team introduced the element of time into the equation as well. They had participants think about either the present or the future (by describing their current residence, or a possible future residence). They found that regardless of mood, long-term, future-focused thinking led to healthier choices.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;When you&rsquo;re in a good mood, you take a longer-term perspective,&rdquo; Gardner says. &ldquo;You see the forest, not the trees... When you&rsquo;re focused on the near term, when you&rsquo;re looking at what&rsquo;s in front of your nose, you respond with what&rsquo;s going to give you quick pleasure. And that&rsquo;s triggered very much by bad moods. But we can fight that.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Dr. Leigh Gibson, a psychology professor at the University of Roehampton in London, disagrees, though he says he finds those results interesting. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not sure that&rsquo;s the way people normally go about their daily eating,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;For habitual behaviors like eating, there tends to be an intention-behavior gap. We have all these wonderful intentions, but when it comes down to it, we&rsquo;re exposed to energy-dense foods when we find ourselves hungry.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">It does seem unlikely that most of us would take the time to describe our future homes to ourselves before deciding on pizza or a salad for lunch. And as previously noted, there is little consensus on what we typically crave when we&rsquo;re happy.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Part of the reason why it seems our moods rarely drive us toward healthy foods, Gibson says, is that for much of human history, energy-dense foods, or what we now consider comfort foods, were the ideal thing to eat.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We didn&rsquo;t evolve as homo sapiens by eating healthy, because all we had to do was reproduce and survive until our mid-20&rsquo;s,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;We were quite happily sucking the marrow out of bones. We were just getting energy, protein, the basic nutrients we needed, but we didn&rsquo;t have to live too long. Healthy eating is a modern, cultural thing that we now need, because we&rsquo;re living so long&hellip; You could almost say the default is comfort eating.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">We&rsquo;re not constantly shoveling mashed potatoes into our mouths (at least not most of the time), so of course this doesn&rsquo;t mean that humans don&rsquo;t ever choose healthy foods, just that when we do, it might not be in response to our emotions.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Another reason for this lack of consensus is that there are a variety of moods that can fit under the &ldquo;positive&rdquo; umbrella&mdash;feeling excited is very different from feeling content, and those emotions could lead to similarly divergent food choices.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">For example, Gardner says we tend to go for special, often unhealthy, foods on celebratory occasions, like birthdays or Thanksgiving.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;You eat the birthday cake, you may go out in the evening and eat more appetizers and drink more cocktails than you intended, and it&rsquo;s all part of the specialness of the occasion,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;And we&rsquo;ve all learned to celebrate with food. It&rsquo;s part of so many different cultures.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Carol Landau&mdash;a clinical professor of psychiatry, human behavior, and medicine at Brown University&mdash;points out that some comfort eaters turn everything into a celebration, rewarding themselves with food not just for special occasions, but for everyday accomplishments as well.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Food is such an important part of culture,&rdquo; Landau says. &ldquo;I think we&rsquo;re asking people to do a lot [by asking them] to avoid comfort eating.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gibson says this sort of celebratory eating seems to be more prevalent for men than women. There&rsquo;s also some evidence that the foods men and women turn to for comfort are different&mdash;men often get more comfort from savory foods and &ldquo;general meal-type foods,&rdquo; Gibson says, as opposed to snacks. Gardner says she has also found men to be more drawn to salty foods.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Sweet foods, however, seem to be a universal crowd-pleaser.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Sweetness is such a powerful stimulus,&rdquo; Gibson says. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re born initially liking sweetness. It probably helps [that babies] have an appetite for breast milk and so on.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">This may well be why the go-to image of comfort eating in culture is someone crying into a pint of Ben &amp; Jerry&rsquo;s, and why so many studies on mood and food choice include chocolate as one of the unhealthy options.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;If one can characterize [comfort] foods in any simple way, it would be that they&rsquo;re typically energy-dense,&rdquo; Gibson says. &ldquo;Therefore they&rsquo;re probably high fat, and they might be sweet as well. The perfect comfort food might be chocolate.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">But as we all know, the positive effects of eating sweets are short-lived. Whether it&rsquo;s a crash that comes after a sugar high, or just a feeling of guilt after eating more cookies than you planned, treats are not a ticket to long-term happiness.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">So in the chicken-or-the-egg problem of food and mood, do the moods hatch the foods, or do the foods hatch the moods? Studies disagree&mdash;the relationship seems to go both ways. A couple recent studies suggest that the foods come first.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">In a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S019566631100643X\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">study published in 2012</a>, Penn State psychology professor Dr. Helen Hendy had 44 undergraduate students keep week-long diaries of how they felt and what they ate. She analyzed the results in terms of four things the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommend we should limit to improve physical health: calories, carbohydrates, saturated fat, and sodium. Following those recommendations, Hendy found, seemed to have benefits for improving moods as well.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">She found that the link between foods and moods played out over a period of two days&mdash;what you ate on day one was linked to how you felt on day three, etc. As usual, the correlation was more consistent with negative moods: &ldquo;Consumption of calories, saturated fat, and sodium was significantly associated with increased negative mood two days later,&rdquo; the study reads.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Some of my research leads me to change my habits, and this one has,&rdquo; Hendy says. &ldquo;I have a big meeting [in two days], so today I&rsquo;m going to watch my calories, my sodium, and my saturated fat, so I can hopefully have a chance to be in a good mood.&rdquo;</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">A similar study,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/bjhp.12021/abstract\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">published in the&nbsp;<em>British Journal of Health Psychology</em></a>&nbsp;in 2013, had 281 undergrads keep a 21-day diary, and did find a correlation between eating fruits and vegetables one day and being in a positive mood the next day. The association with eating fruit was stronger for men, but both men and women benefitted from eating veggies. Participants&rsquo; BMI did not affect the association.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">The exact reasons why healthy eating might make you happy are unclear, but Gibson posits that if you intend to eat healthily, and you follow through, that could put you in a good mood. &ldquo;Achieving goals is part and parcel of emotional experience,&rdquo; he says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Both eating and emotion are such regular, consistent parts of our lives that it&rsquo;s inevitable they would get tangled up together. Unfortunately, though research has illuminated some interesting possibilities as to how they relate to one another, the knot is still very much intact and it&rsquo;s hard to see where one ends and the other begins.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;There&rsquo;s not a very neat story there,&rdquo; Gibson says. Regardless, there&rsquo;s a bit more to it than just feeling sad and therefore reaching for a spoon and some ice cream, or whatever your preferred unhealthy snack is. It seems entirely possible that all eating is, in fact, emotional eating.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\"><strong>Source</strong>:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/our-moods-our-foods/284238/\">https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/our-moods-our-foods/284238/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">1)&nbsp; According to the text what are the emotions linked to the necessity of eating?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp; In the song,&nbsp;<strong>The Food Song</strong>, what are the reasons that lead the protagonist to eat?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">3)&nbsp;&nbsp; And you, what are the emotions that affect your diet? Explain: What are your food choices in different situations?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4)&nbsp;&nbsp; Are you an emotional eater? &nbsp;Why?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(2,84,'Atividade 1: Partes do corpo','<p>Observe as partes do corpo.</p>\r\n'),(2,85,'Atividade 2: Complete com as partes do corpo','<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/BODY%201.JPG\" style=\"height:523px; width:594px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/HEAD%202.JPG\" style=\"height:520px; width:606px\" /></p>\r\n'),(2,86,'Atividade 3: Vamos praticar!','<p>Digite a resposta correta nos espa&ccedil;os em branco: must - can&#39;t - might</p>\r\n'),(2,87,'Atividade 4: Sobre racismo','<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">One of the social issues addressed by the story is that of racism. As it is well known, racism consists in the belief of a supposed supremacy of one race over another. Although there are various campaigns to combat racism in different parts of the world, this is a practice that still manifests itself in different ways in our daily lives. Could you tell us how these practices materialize in the story presented? Why does it happen?</p>\r\n'),(2,88,'Atividade 5: Leia o texto','<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">As mentioned before, racist practices manifest themselves in different ways, one of which is in the strangeness of certain languages&nbsp;and / or&nbsp;linguistic practices. In the English language, some of their speakers suffer from racism simply because they speak differently from what is considered standard English. Have you ever heard about African English? How Let&rsquo;s learn a little about this variant?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\"><strong>Read the text and answer the following questions.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">What is Ebonics (African American English)?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:90pt\">By John R. Rickford</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">At its most literal level, Ebonics simply means &#39;black speech&#39; (a blend of the words ebony &#39;black&#39; and phonics &#39;sounds&#39;). The term was created in 1973 by a group of black scholars who disliked the negative connotations of terms like &#39;Nonstandard Negro English&#39; that had been coined in the 1960s when the first modern large-scale linguistic studies of African American speech-communities began. However, the term Ebonics never caught on among linguists, much less among the general public. That all changed with the &#39;Ebonics&#39; controversy of December 1996 when the Oakland (CA) School Board recognized it as the &#39;primary&#39; language of its majority African American students and resolved to take it into account in teaching them standard or academic English.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">1____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">Ebonics pronunciation includes features like the omission of the final consonant in words like &#39;past&#39; (pas&#39; ) and &#39;hand&#39; (han&#39;), the pronunciation of the&nbsp;th in&nbsp;&#39;bath&#39; as t (bat) or f (baf), and the pronunciation of the vowel in words like &#39;my&#39; and &#39;ride&#39; as a long ah (mah,&nbsp;rahd). Some of these occur in vernacular white English, too, especially in the South, but in&nbsp;general&nbsp;they occur more frequently in Ebonics. Some Ebonics pronunciations are more unique, for instance, dropping b, d,&nbsp;or g&nbsp;at the beginning of auxiliary verbs like &#39;don&#39;t&#39; and &#39;gonna&#39;, yielding Ah &#39;on know for &quot;I don&#39;t know&quot; and ama do it for &quot;I&#39;m going to do it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">2____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">These distinctive Ebonics pronunciations are all systematic, the result of regular rules and restrictions; they are not random &#39;error&#39;--and this is equally true of Ebonics grammar. For instance, Ebonics speakers regularly produce sentences without present tense is and are, as in &quot;John&nbsp;trippin&quot; or &quot;They&nbsp;allright&quot;. But they don&#39;t omit present tense am. Instead of the ungrammatical *&quot;Ah&nbsp;walkin&quot;, Ebonics speakers would say *&quot;Ahm&nbsp;walkin.&quot; Likewise, they do not omit is and are if they come at the end of a sentence--&quot;That&#39;s what he/they&quot; is ungrammatical. Many members of the public seem to have heard, too, that Ebonics speakers use an &#39;invariant&#39; be in their speech (as in &quot;They be&nbsp;goin&nbsp;to school every day&quot;); however, this&nbsp;be&nbsp;is not simply equivalent to is or are. Invariant&nbsp;be refers&nbsp;to actions that occur regularly or habitually rather than on just one occasion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">3____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">That depends on whom you ask. Black writers from Paul Laurence Dunbar to Zora Neale Hurston to August Wilson have made extensive use of it in their work, and some, like James Baldwin (&quot;this passion, this skill, ... this incredible music.&quot;), Toni Morrison, and June Jordan have praised it explicitly. Black preachers and comedians and singers, especially rappers, also use it for&nbsp;dramatic&nbsp;or realistic effect. But many other people, black and white, regard it as a sign of limited education or sophistication, as a legacy of slavery or an impediment to socioeconomic mobility. Some deny its existence (like the black Chicagoan whose words &quot;Ain&#39;t nobody here talkin&#39; no Ebonics&quot; belied his claim). Others deprecate it (like Maya Angelou, who found the Oakland School Board&#39;s 1996 Ebonics resolutions &quot;very threatening&quot; although she uses Ebonics herself in her poems, e.g. &quot;The Pusher&quot;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">4____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">On this point, linguists are quite divided. Some emphasize its English origins, pointing to the fact that most of the vocabulary of Ebonics is from English and that much of its pronunciation (e.g. pronouncing final&nbsp;th&nbsp;as f) and grammar (e.g. double negatives, &quot;I don&#39;t want none&quot;) could have come from the nonstandard dialects of English indentured servants and other workers with whom African slaves interacted. Others emphasize Ebonics&#39; African origins, noting that West African languages often lack&nbsp;th&nbsp;sounds and final consonant clusters (e.g. past),&nbsp;and that replacing or simplifying these occurs both in US Ebonics and in West African English varieties spoken in Nigeria and Ghana.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">(Adapted&nbsp;from:&nbsp;https://www.linguisticsociety.org/content/what-ebonics-african-american-english )</p>\r\n'),(2,89,'Atividade 1: Escuta e repetição','<p>Escute&nbsp;e repita os di&aacute;logos</p>\r\n'),(2,91,'Atividade 2 - Reflita','<p>You&rsquo;ve probably noticed that the use of &ldquo;she&rdquo; referring to the actor&rsquo;s partner caused embarrassment to the actor, whose partner is a man, not a woman. So the question is: which pronoun &ndash; &ldquo;he&rdquo;, &ldquo;she&rdquo; or &ldquo;they&rdquo; &ndash; should be used with reference to words that can refer to both genders, like &ldquo;partner&rdquo;, &ldquo;student&rdquo;, &ldquo;teacher&rdquo;, &ldquo;colleague&rdquo;, &ldquo;author&rdquo;, &ldquo;doctor&rdquo;, &ldquo;person&rdquo;, among so many others? In other words, how can gender bias be avoided? For many years, people tended to use &ldquo;he&rdquo; (and &ldquo;him&rdquo;, &ldquo;his&rdquo;, &ldquo;himself&rdquo;) to refer to such words, for example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since&nbsp;<em>he</em>&nbsp;may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in&nbsp;<em>his</em>&nbsp;findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, this is considered to be sexist and instead, therefore some people use &ldquo;he or&nbsp;she&rdquo;:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since&nbsp;<em>he or she</em>&nbsp;may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in&nbsp;<em>his or her</em>&nbsp;findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem is that frequent repetition of &ldquo;he or she&rdquo; slows down reading and writing. Therefore, people may choose to use third person plural pronouns: &ldquo;they&rdquo;, &ldquo;them&rdquo;, &ldquo;their&rdquo;, &ldquo;theirs&rdquo; and &ldquo;themselves&rdquo; (or &ldquo;themself&rdquo; in informal contexts). Although the use of plural pronouns to refer back to a singular subject may seem wrong, it&rsquo;s increasingly common in both written and spoken English:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since&nbsp;<em>they</em>&nbsp;may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in&nbsp;<em>their</em>&nbsp;findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Can you think of other gender-neutral words? Do you believe using gender-neutral words and pronouns can help avoid sexist&nbsp;behaviour&nbsp;in general? Why (not)? In the following article, published by &ldquo;The Guardian&rdquo;, the author suggests&nbsp;that&nbsp; gender&nbsp;is a &ldquo;primary way of signifying relationships of power&rdquo;. Do you agree?&nbsp; Read the article by clicking on:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/may/05/they-the-singular-pronoun-that-could-solve-sexism-in-english\">www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/may/05/they-the-singular-pronoun-that-could-solve-sexism-in-english</a></p>\r\n'),(2,92,'Atividade 3','<p>When the TV presenter asked the actor how he got the role, he answered: &ldquo;One day my agent just&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\"><strong>called&nbsp;</strong></span>me to say that they&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\"><strong>were staging</strong></span>&nbsp;an adaptation of Jessica Richmond&rsquo;s novel&rdquo;. Can you tell the difference between the verb tenses underlined above?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Were staging&rdquo; (Past Continuous) suggests something that was happening around a particular point in the past, whereas &ldquo;called&rdquo; (Past Simple) expresses the idea of a short action.&nbsp; These tenses are often used together, as in: &ldquo;I played Stanley in &ldquo;A streetcar named Desire&rdquo; two years ago, and&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\"><strong>was preparing</strong></span>&nbsp;for my first movie role when the audition&nbsp;<strong><span class=\"marker\">came up</span></strong>.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In cases like this, the&nbsp;Past Continuous&nbsp;describes a longer, background action and the&nbsp;Past Simple&nbsp;describes the events.</p>\r\n'),(2,93,'Atividade 4','<p>Bearing in mind what you learned in Activities 3 and 4, say what was happening in each of the pictures below:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/cellular-education-classroom-159844.jpeg\" style=\"height:387px; width:580px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ex: The teacher was writing on the board while the student was texting</p>\r\n'),(2,94,'Atividade 5','<p>Can you guess what the following underlined expressions mean?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I was preparing for my first movie role when the audition&nbsp;<u>came up</u>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I think women have to&nbsp;<u>stand up for</u>&nbsp;their rights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The expressions underlined are known as phrasal verbs. Phrasal verbs are combinations of verbs with prepositions (ex: for), adverbs (ex: up) or both (ex: up for) that function as verbs which have meanings different from the meaning of the words considered separately. In the first case, &ldquo;came up&rdquo; means &ldquo;became available&rdquo;, and in the second, &ldquo;stand up for&rdquo; means &ldquo;defend&rdquo;. Here are a few other phrasal verbs you may know:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Can you&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/turn_1\">turn</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<u>up</u>&nbsp;the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/volume\">air</a>&nbsp;conditioner a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/bit_1\">bit</a>?&nbsp; (to increase the amount of sound, heat or light by pressing a button)</li>\r\n	<li>Will you&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/turn_1\">turn</a>&nbsp;the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/music\">music</a>&nbsp;<u>down</u>&nbsp;a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/bit_1\">bit</a>? (to reduce the amount of sound, heat or light by pressing a button)</li>\r\n	<li>Why did you&nbsp;<u>turn down</u>&nbsp;that fantastic offer? (to not accept an offer or request)</li>\r\n	<li>Frank is the most sociable person I know &ndash; he&nbsp;<u>gets on</u>&nbsp;with everyone (to have a good relationship with someone)</li>\r\n	<li>How do politicians&nbsp;<u>get away with</u>&nbsp;corruption? (to manage to do something bad without being punished or&nbsp;criticised&nbsp;for it)</li>\r\n	<li>Chris lost five kilos since she&nbsp;<u>took up</u>&nbsp;jogging. (to start doing something as a habit, job or interest)</li>\r\n	<li>I can&rsquo;t&nbsp;<u>take on</u>&nbsp;any more work right now. (to accept work or responsibility)</li>\r\n	<li>Sam started his business five years ago but it only&nbsp;<u>took off</u>&nbsp;last year. (to start to be successful or popular)</li>\r\n	<li>I&nbsp;<u>took to</u>&nbsp;Sarah immediately.(to begin to like someone or something)</li>\r\n	<li>We were terribly worried but t<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/thing\">hings</a>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/work_1\">worked</a><u>&nbsp;out</u>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/pretty_1\">pretty</a>&nbsp;well in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/end_1\">end</a>. (to be&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/successful\">successful</a>, or to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/end_1\">end</a>&nbsp;in a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/particular_1\">particular</a>&nbsp;way)</li>\r\n	<li>Children often&nbsp;<u>look up to</u>&nbsp;Brazilian footballers. (to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/admire\">admire</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/respect_1\">respect</a>&nbsp;someone)</li>\r\n	<li>You shouldn&rsquo;t&nbsp;<u>look down on</u>&nbsp;people who don&rsquo;t earn as much as you do. (to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/think_1\">think</a>&nbsp;that you are&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/better_1\">better</a>&nbsp;or more&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/important\">important</a>&nbsp;than someone else, or to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/think_1\">think</a>&nbsp;that something is not&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/good_1\">good</a>&nbsp;enough for you)</li>\r\n	<li>At&nbsp;first&nbsp;I didn&rsquo;t&nbsp;<u>catch on</u>&nbsp;what his real intentions were. (to understand)</li>\r\n	<li>I had to&nbsp;<u>make up</u>&nbsp;an excuse about losing my key. (to invent a story, or explanation for something, in order to avoid being punished for something)</li>\r\n	<li>The children&nbsp;<u>made off</u>&nbsp;when they heard their parents arrive. (to leave quickly, especially after doing something wrong)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The list of phrasal verbs in English is really long, and the same phrasal verb may have several meanings (as is the case of &ldquo;turn down&rdquo;, for example, as well as most of the other phrasal verbs above). The best way of learning them is by paying attention to the contexts in which they are used. In the next activity you&rsquo;ll have a chance to practice some of them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(2,103,'Atividade 1','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif\"><strong>Na maioria das vezes, as defini&ccedil;&otilde;es do dicion&aacute;rio s&atilde;o simplificadas demais e incompletas. Veja a defini&ccedil;&atilde;o de &quot;multiculturalismo&quot; apresentada pelo Dicion&aacute;rio Macmillan, e uma explica&ccedil;&atilde;o expandida e mais completa do termo.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0)\">Macmillan dictionary:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0)\">multiculturalism - the belief and practice of giving equal importance to each of the different cultures in a society</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0)\">Expanded definition:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0)\">The term &lsquo;multiculturalism&rsquo; is sometimes used to describe a condition of society; more precisely, it is used to describe a society where a variety of different cultures coexist. Many countries in the world are culturally diverse. Canada is just one example, including a variety of cultures such as English Canadians, Quebecois, Native Americans, Amish, Hutterites and Chinese immigrants. (...) There are a variety of ways whereby societies can be diverse, for example, culture can come in many forms (Gurr, 1993, p. 3). (...) Religious diversity is a widespread phenomenon in many countries. India can be given as an example of a country which is religiously diverse, including citizens who are Sikhs, Hindus, Buddhists, among other religious groups. (...) Linguistic diversity is also widespread. In the 21st century, there are more than 200 countries in the world and around 6000 spoken languages (Laitin, 2007). Linguistic diversity usually results from two kinds of groups. (...) The second kind of groups that are a cause of linguistic diversity are national minorities. National minorities are groups that have either settled in the country for a long time, but do not share the same language with the majority. (...) A third kind of group diversity can result from distinct territory location. This territory location does not necessarily mean that members of distinct cultures are, in fact, different. That is, it is not necessary that habits, traditions, customs, and so forth are significantly different. However, these distinct groups identify themselves as different from others because of the specific geographical area in which they are located. (...) The fourth kind of group diversity is race. Races are groups whose physical characteristics are imbued with social significance. In other words, race is a socially constructed concept in the sense that it is the result of individuals giving social significance to a set of characteristics they consider that stand out in a person&#39;s physical appearance, such as skin color, eye color, hair color, bone/jaw structure and so forth. However, the mere existence of different physical characteristics does not mean that there is a multicultural environment/society. (...) That is, racial cultural diversity is not simply the existence of different physical characteristics. Rather, these different physical characteristics must entail a sense of common identity which, in turn, are socially perceived as something that differentiates the members of that group to others. (...) The social significance given to these physical differences are sufficient for members of both groups, broadly speaking, to identify as members of one group or the other, and subsequently oppose to each other. (</span><a href=\"https://www.iep.utm.edu/multicul/#H2\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204)\">https://www.iep.utm.edu/multicul/#H2</span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0)\">)&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif\"><strong><em>Agora, escreva defini&ccedil;&otilde;es expandidas para as seguintes defini&ccedil;&otilde;es de dicion&aacute;rio:</em></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(2,104,'Atividade 2','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">No v&iacute;deo, Helena e Caetano falam sobre a salad bowl dizendo que &quot;Our family is such a salad bowl we can practically cover the whole world with it&quot;. Considerando o contexto da fam&iacute;lia deles, o que voc&ecirc; entende por essa express&atilde;o? Voc&ecirc; acha que &eacute; similar ou diferente do conceito de melting pot?</span></p>\r\n'),(2,120,'Atividade 4: Wrapping it up!','<p>As situa&ccedil;&otilde;es apresentadas nos audios 1, 2 e 3 nos fazem pensar em (im)possibilidades enunciativas, ou seja, no fato de que nem tudo pode ser dito &ndash; seja em l&iacute;ngua materna ou estrangeira. E tal impossibilidade deve-se n&atilde;o apenas por uma suposta falta de profici&ecirc;ncia do falante, mas a fatores que remetem &agrave; rela&ccedil;&atilde;o da l&iacute;ngua com a hist&oacute;ria, dos sentidos com os quais os sujeitos se identificam, das condi&ccedil;&otilde;es de produ&ccedil;&atilde;o da enuncia&ccedil;&atilde;o (que s&atilde;o &uacute;nicas e irrepet&iacute;veis), das imagens que o interlocutor tem de si e do(s) outro(s). Ademais, h&aacute; de se considerar que essas (im)possibilidades dizem respeito &agrave; natureza sempre tensa e conflitiva da tomada significante da palavra, j&aacute; que, ao significar o mundo, nos significamos &lsquo;no&rsquo; mundo. Ou seja, ao dizer (d)o outro, digo de mim, me posiciono em rela&ccedil;&atilde;o ao outro e o posiciono em rela&ccedil;&atilde;o a mim.</p>\r\n'),(2,121,'Atividade 6: Deduções por modais','<p>Usamos os verbos modais para dizer qu&atilde;o certos estamos sobre algo</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>must </strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use must when we feel sure that something is true because there&rsquo;s very strong evidence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He must live near here because he comes to work on foot. We don&rsquo;t know where he lives but we&rsquo;re sure it&rsquo;s not far away.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Come inside and get warm &ndash; you must be freezing out there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&rsquo;re a zookeeper? That must be very interesting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notice that must is followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>might, may, could</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use might, may or could to say that we think something is possible but we&rsquo;re not sure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Did you hear that? I think there might be a burglar downstairs. She&rsquo;s not sure there&rsquo;s a burglar but she thinks it&rsquo;s possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ll try to get there early but we may arrive late if there&rsquo;s a lot of traffic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t put it up there. It could fall off and hit someone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Might, may and could are also followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>can&rsquo;t</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use can&rsquo;t when we feel sure something is not true.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It can&rsquo;t be a burglar. All the doors and windows are locked. He doesn&rsquo;t know it&rsquo;s not a burglar but he feels sure it&rsquo;s not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It can&rsquo;t be far away now. We&rsquo;ve been driving for hours. Where&rsquo;s the map?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Really? He has to work on Christmas Day? He can&rsquo;t feel very happy about that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like the other verbs, can&rsquo;t is followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n'),(2,122,'Atividade 7: Reflita a respeito','<p>Usando suas pr&oacute;prias palavras, voc&ecirc; poderia nos dizer o que &eacute; &#39;Ebonics&#39;?</p>\r\n'),(2,135,'Prática de pronúncia de fonemas de vogais','<p>Nesta atividade, convidamos voc&ecirc; a assistir os v&iacute;deos com algumas vogais e palavras de exemplo das vogais e repeti-las. Vamos l&aacute;?</p>\r\n'),(2,140,'Atividade 2: Diferentes formulações','<p><em>Quais outras formula&ccedil;&otilde;es poder&iacute;amos dizer para completar os bal&otilde;es e manter o tom amig&aacute;vel das conversas originais das personagens? Para cada lacuna, escolha uma das 03 op&ccedil;&otilde;es propostas e fale-a em seu microfone para obter um feedback. &Agrave;s vezes, mais de uma op&ccedil;&atilde;o &eacute; correta.</em></p>\r\n'),(2,142,'Atividade 3','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\">A mudan&ccedil;a de c&oacute;digo &eacute; um fen&ocirc;meno lingu&iacute;stico em que as pessoas mudam a forma como falam para um modo de falar mais formal ou informal. &Eacute; tamb&eacute;m um fen&oacute;meno em que as pessoas usam duas ou mais l&iacute;nguas para comunicar umas com as outras.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Como vimos no v&iacute;deo, Helena e Caetano vivem num ambiente translingu&iacute;stico porque usam tr&ecirc;s l&iacute;nguas, por vezes numa frase, para falar uma com a outra.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Escreva um texto explicando o que voc&ecirc; entende por ambiente translingu&iacute;stico e comuta&ccedil;&atilde;o de c&oacute;digo. Voc&ecirc; consegue pensar em aspectos positivos de empregar a troca de c&oacute;digo regularmente? E os aspectos negativos?</span></p>\r\n'),(2,144,'Atividade 4','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><em>Nos estudos de Bot&acirc;nica, o rizoma &eacute; o principal caule da planta. &Eacute; a parte da planta respons&aacute;vel por permitir que as ra&iacute;zes cres&ccedil;am e se espalhem.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/rizoma.jpg\" style=\"height:300px; width:297px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><em>Podemos entender a fam&iacute;lia como um rizoma. &Eacute; a parte da nossa vida que nos permite crescer; e &eacute; por isso que dizemos que todos os membros da nossa fam&iacute;lia fazem parte da nossa &aacute;rvore geneal&oacute;gica.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><em>Quando Helena e Caetano nos apresentaram sua fam&iacute;lia, pudemos perceber o quanto ela &eacute; extensa. Assista o v&iacute;deo novamente e combine o nome das pessoas da hist&oacute;ria e sua rela&ccedil;&atilde;o familiar com os demais.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Eron</em><em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</em><em>Julia</em><em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</em><em>Pilar</em><em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</em><em>Helena&nbsp; Caetano</em><em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Ex.: Helena = Irm&atilde; do Caetano</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Filha da Julia e do Eron</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Irm&atilde; da Pilar</em></p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n'),(2,147,'Videoaula de fonética e fonologia do inglês','<p>Videoaula</p>\r\n'),(2,152,'Atividade 1','<p><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">In the animation</span><em>&nbsp;Art for Thought</em><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">, the characters talk about the art exhibits they saw. They give their opinions and describe their feelings. In the snippet below, we underlined the expressions that express their feelings and opinions and made bold the adjectives and adverbs they used:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Nadine: _ So, what are your thoughts on the exbhibitions we&acute;ve just seen?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Daniel: _&nbsp;</span><u><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">I was particularly&nbsp;</span><strong>impressed</strong></u><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">&nbsp;by the collages of parts of the body and poems.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Rosa: _ How come?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Daniel: _&nbsp;</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">They were somehow&nbsp;</span><strong>disconcerting</strong><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">&nbsp;to me</span></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. The words of the poems and the quotes resignified those sad, morbid organs into something else, but after reading the stories of the patients, I gained a whole new perspective.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Ben&iacute;cio: _&nbsp;<u>Yeah,&nbsp;</u></span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">that was&nbsp;</span><strong>very</strong><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">&nbsp;</span><strong>impressive</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">.&nbsp;</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">This visit was&nbsp;</span><strong>interesting and thought-provoking</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. It was a great break from our readings and discussions.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Rosa: _ For sure.&nbsp;<u>The second exhibit made it feel like&nbsp;</u>recess time to me.&nbsp;</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">All the pieces</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">were&nbsp;</span><strong>absolutely beautiful</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Nadine: _</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">I think that&rsquo;s exactly&nbsp;</span></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">what art can do to us: to give us a break, to inspire, to</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">unsettle, to shake us and make us feel alive. It opens up room for new thoughts</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">and understandings.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Ben&iacute;cio: _</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">I felt more&nbsp;</span><strong>emotional</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">&nbsp;when I saw the video installations.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Daniel: _ Yes,&nbsp;</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">they were&nbsp;</span><strong>very touching</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Nadine: _&nbsp;</span><strong>I loved the paintings</strong><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. Those colors&nbsp;</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">really had an impact on me</span></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. It was like they could move and invade my soul.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Rosa: _ Yes, those large pieces&nbsp;</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">make us feel like</span></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">&nbsp;we are&nbsp;</span><em>in</em><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">&nbsp;the paintings.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">The underlined and bolded words in the snippet can be organized as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/quadro%20unit%207.JPG\" style=\"height:286px; width:648px\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other examples of verbs to express feelings</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Pleasant feelings: like, enjoy, appreciate</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Unpleasant feelings: dislike, hate, fear</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other adjectives to talk about art:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Pleasant and positive feelings: Calm, cheerful, content, energetic, exciting, happy, joyful, peaceful,relaxed, stimulating, thought-provoking, tranquil</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Unpleasant feelings: aggressive, angry, bored/boring, chilling, dark, depressing/depressed, distressing, dull, frightening, gloomy, insipid, lifeless,&nbsp; miserable, sad, somber, tearful, violent, unhappy&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other examples of expressions to talk about art:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">The work is really something to behold.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It is full of meaning and emotion.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It is the portrayal of a real-life observation.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It demonstrates the emotion of the artist.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It immersed me in a reflective journey.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">The work is of exceptional beauty.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It inspired me.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It transforms the visible world.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Agora, vamos praticar dar opini&otilde;es e defender nossas ideias. Leia as perguntas e use a ferramenta de grava&ccedil;&atilde;o para registrar suas respostas.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Qual sua opini&atilde;o sobre essas imagens?&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:16px\">Como voc&ecirc; se sente ao olhar para elas?</span></p>\r\n'),(2,153,'Atividade 1: Atividade de relacionar itens das colunas','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">&ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women (2018 version)&rdquo; is a short animation that tells us about the daily routines of four female characters: Ana, Maria, Lucia and Stela, who portray situations that many real women experience in their lives. They are hardworking, dignified people who have to </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">put up with</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"> </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">sexism</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"> and oppression in forms that vary from minor offenses to sexual harassment and violence.&nbsp; </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\" style=\"margin-left:222.75pt;\">\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse:collapse; border:none\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p><strong>Quick notes:</strong></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Put up with</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> (/ˈpʊtˈʌp</span><a href=\"https://easypronunciation.com/\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">ˈwɪ&theta;/)</span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> = tolerate, endure</span></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Sexism </strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">(/ˈsekˌsizəm/)= prejudice, discrimination or stereotyping based on sexual identifications</span></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Harassment</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> (/həˈrasmənt,ˈherəsmənt/) = intimidation or aggressive behavior that demeans, humiliates or embarrasses a person</span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">But&nbsp; what can be considered harassment? How does it take place? Let us read this definition by the United Nations Entity for Gender Equality and the Empowerment of Women:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Text 1</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><strong>Prohibition of discrimination, harassment, including sexual harassment, and abuse of authority</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Discrimination, sexual harassment and harassment are defined in SG&#39;s bulletin</span><a href=\"http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&amp;DS=ST/SGB/2008/5&amp;Lang=E\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\"> </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">ST/SGB/2008/5</span></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Discrimination is any unfair treatment or arbitrary distinction based on a person&rsquo;s race, sex, religion, nationality, ethnic origin, sexual orientation, disability, age, language, social origin or other status. Discrimination may be an isolated event affecting one person or a group of persons similarly situated, or may manifest itself through harassment or abuse of authority.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Harassment is any improper and unwelcome conduct that might reasonably be expected or be perceived to cause offence or humiliation to another person. Harassment may take the form of words, gestures or actions which tend to annoy, alarm, abuse, demean, intimidate, belittle, humiliate or embarrass another or which create an intimidating, hostile or offensive work environment. Harassment normally implies a series of incidents. Disagreement on work performance or on other work-related issues is normally not considered harassment and is not dealt with under the provisions of this policy but in the context of performance management.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Sexual harassment is any unwelcome sexual advance, request for sexual favour, verbal or physical conduct or gesture of a sexual nature, or any other behaviour of a sexual nature that might reasonably be expected or be perceived to cause offence or humiliation to another, when such conduct interferes with work, is made a condition of employment or creates an intimidating, hostile or offensive work environment. While typically involving a pattern of behaviour, it can take the form of a single incident. Sexual harassment may occur between persons of the opposite or same sex. Both males and females can be either the victims or the offenders.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">Source: </span><a href=\"https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/fpsexualharassment.htm\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/fpsexualharassment.htm</span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">. Access: 07/07/2019.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Given this explanation on the terms&nbsp;</span><em>discrimination</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">,&nbsp;</span><em>harassment</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">, and&nbsp;</span><em>abuse</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">, let&acute;s review some moments in the narrative of &ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women (2018)&rdquo; that portray situations what we consider to be cases of harassment; sexual harassent, and abuse. Which vocabulary in the left column do you consider express the situations portrayed in the scenes on the right column?</span></p>\r\n'),(2,155,'Atividade 2','<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Assista a anima&ccedil;&atilde;o </span><em>Art for thought</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"> novamente. Ou&ccedil;a, pause e repita o di&aacute;logo das personagens.</span></p>\r\n'),(2,158,'Atividade 3 : Exercício de resposta dissertativa','<p>Now, it is your turn. Describe the day of a woman that you know (your mother, a friend, your sister, or you can describe your own day) using 5 different verbs. You can use the verbs suggested in the list.</p>\r\n'),(2,159,'Atividade 2: Preenchimento de balões','<p>The box below brings back the narrator ́s text in the animation &ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women&rdquo;. Complete the blanks with the verbs in parentheses in their appropriate conjugation.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:633px\">\r\n			<p><strong><u>Ana</u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>It&rsquo;s morning. We ______(see) Ana, our first character, preparing to go to work. She chooses a piece of clothing. But then, she ______ (notice) she may need to dress in more formal attire. She ______ (get) to work on time, and she ______ (work) hard, as always. She is one of the computer programmer chiefs in a big company. She assigns, coordinates, and reviews the work of her programming team. She has to analyze each product demand, suggest creative ways to develop it, and make the final decisions for the most efficient solutions. Attending meetings with her boss is one of her usual activities. Ana ______ (be) one of the very few women to be in a leadership position in the area of IT. Not only do men tend to rephrase her ideas, they also avoid give her credit for them. And they ______ (try) to oppress her by diverging the attention to stereotypical matters.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong><u>Maria</u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Our next strong female character is Maria. She is a single parent. She was abandoned by her violent partner, and she ______(raise) her daughter Matilda alone. They ______ (wake) up early so Maria can leave Matilda at day care before going to work. After leaving Matilda at daycare, Maria ______ (take) the bus to go to work. She ______(work) full time as a security guard. Maria is very vigilant and concerned with protecting women from abuse. After picking up Matilda, Maria still has some chores to do: she has to do her grocery shopping, clean the house, and after playing with Matilda, put her to bed. The most frightful thing is when Maria ______ (fall) asleep, but has nightmares with her ex-partner, who used to beat her.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong><u>Lucia</u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Among our hardworking, strong female characters, we have Lucia. She is editor-in-chief of a major book publisher. She works full time in the same building Ana and Maria ______ (work). Lucia is over her 40s now. She is single and very committed to work. She has a brilliant career in a job she ______ (love), but she is usually expected to fulfill a certain representation of women in a patriarchal model of society. Besides spending time with her parents sometimes, Lucia has an intense social and professional life. And sometimes she freely just ______ (choose) to be by herself.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong><u>Stela</u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Our last female character in this story is Stela. Stela is 16 years old. She is a great, passionate violin player. She ______ (practice) every day after school. As every woman, she has to put up with very offensive harassment and attempts to make her invisible and explored. When she ______ (play) the violin though, she ______ (find) her own, peaceful and safe place.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(2,160,'Atividade 3','<p><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Repita as frases que voc&ecirc; ouve. Certifique-se de reproduzir a entona&ccedil;&atilde;o que voc&ecirc; ouve e as express&otilde;es faciais dos atores nos v&iacute;deos:</span></p>\r\n'),(2,161,'Atividade 4: Expressing emotions','<p>Complete the sentences with the correct adjective:</p>\r\n'),(2,162,'Prática de pronúncia de fonemas de vogais 2','<p>Nesta atividade, vamos continuar a realizar as repeti&ccedil;&otilde;es vogais. Vamos l&aacute;?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/u:/ root​&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ʊ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ cook&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɔ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ caught&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɜ:</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ urban&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ə</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ annoy&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">ʌ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/ hut</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n'),(2,163,'Atividade 5: Resposta dissertativa oral','<p>In what other situations do you feel&hellip; (mention at least one situation).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Example: I feel happy when I go to a wedding.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type:lower-alpha\">\r\n	<li>happy?</li>\r\n	<li>frightened?</li>\r\n	<li>angry?</li>\r\n	<li>disgusted?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n'),(2,166,'Atividade 6: Resposta dissertativa','<p>What emojis can we use to describe the emotions expressed in the previous exercise (happy, disgusted, frightened, and angry)? Select at least two emojis for each emotion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/atv6_1.png\" style=\"height:121px; width:648px\" /></p>\r\n'),(2,167,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 1','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Segundo Dinah Callou &amp; Yonne Leite (1993), enquanto a fon&eacute;tica estuda os sons como entidades fisico-articulat&oacute;rias isoladas, a fonologia estuda os sons do ponto de vista funcional, como elementos integrantes de um sistema lingu&iacute;stico. A fon&eacute;tica visa descrever os sons e analisar suas particularidades articulat&oacute;rias, ac&uacute;sticas e perceptivas. Enquanto isso, a fonologia estuda diferen&ccedil;as fonol&oacute;gicas intencionais, que podem estar associadas a diferen&ccedil;as de significado. Essas duas disciplinas s&atilde;o vistas como interdependentes, uma vez que para os estudos fonol&oacute;gicos &eacute; preciso levar em considera&ccedil;&atilde;o os aspectos fon&eacute;ticos, ac&uacute;sticos e/ou articulat&oacute;rios, a fim de determinar as unidades distintivas (fonemas) em uma determinada l&iacute;ngua.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Como o fonema &eacute; a menor unidade sonora em uma l&iacute;ngua, capaz de transmitir um significado distinto, nessa atividade voc&ecirc; vai praticar todos os 44 fonemas mapeados no idioma ingl&ecirc;s.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Primeiro, vamos nos concentrar nos fonemas consonantais. Uma consoante &eacute; um som em que h&aacute; obstru&ccedil;&atilde;o ou bloqueio do fluxo de ar durante a passagem dos pulm&otilde;es pelo aparelho vocal.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Em cada v&iacute;deo, voc&ecirc; ouvir&aacute; uma palavra em que os diferentes sons consonantais s&atilde;o produzidos e, nas legendas, voc&ecirc; ver&aacute; o fonema destacado e a palavra completa.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Observe que os fonemas s&atilde;o s&iacute;mbolos que est&atilde;o entre as barras / /. A maioria dos s&iacute;mbolos usados ​​para representar os sons &eacute; a mesma das letras usadas no alfabeto latino, mas tamb&eacute;m h&aacute; outros s&iacute;mbolos e cada s&iacute;mbolo &eacute; atribu&iacute;do a um som espec&iacute;fico.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Reproduza o v&iacute;deo, ou&ccedil;a a palavra e a pron&uacute;ncia do fonema, depois grave a sua pr&oacute;pria voz para feedback. </span></p>\r\n'),(2,168,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 2','<p>Nesta atividade , vamos continuar a praticar a pron&uacute;ncia de fonemas consonantais. Focaremos nos seguintes fonemas e exemplos de palavras:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54.0pt\"><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; /f/ for&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /v/ vibrant&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /&theta;/ thick&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /&eth;/ the</p>\r\n'),(2,171,'teste colunas','<p>descri&ccedil;&atilde;o</p>\r\n'),(2,172,'Atividade 5','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">As pessoas deixam os seus pa&iacute;ses por muitas raz&otilde;es diferentes, como fez Eron. Algumas delas mudam-se para outro pa&iacute;s &agrave; procura de uma vida melhor, com melhores oportunidades de emprego e melhores oportunidades de prosperar. Outros se mudam para outro pa&iacute;s para sobreviver, fugindo de guerras, conflitos e desastres. Combine as colunas com as melhores defini&ccedil;&otilde;es para as palavras relacionadas com os diferentes tipos de pessoas que migram para outro pa&iacute;s.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Source: https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-46747502</p>\r\n'),(2,173,'Atividade 6','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Agora que voc&ecirc; associou as defini&ccedil;&otilde;es, responda &agrave;s perguntas abaixo gravando &aacute;udios para cada pergunta.</span></p>\r\n'),(2,174,'Atividade 7 - Combine as colunas','<p>Combine a express&atilde;o idiom&aacute;tica com o seu significado.</p>\r\n'),(2,178,'Atividade 7','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Relacione o pa&iacute;s com a nacionalidade correspondente.</span></p>\r\n'),(2,179,'Atividade 5: Análise de Emoção da Voz','<p>An&aacute;lise de Emo&ccedil;&atilde;o da Voz</p>\r\n'),(2,180,'Atividade 7: Múltipla escolha','<p>Existem outras formas de expressar emo&ccedil;&otilde;es em nossa&nbsp;escrita&nbsp;tamb&eacute;m.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Qual seria a resposta apropriada para expressar emo&ccedil;&otilde;es nas seguintes situa&ccedil;&otilde;es? Mais de uma resposta &eacute; poss&iacute;vel.</p>\r\n'),(2,182,'Atividade 8 - Praticando os Modais','<p>Escolha a melhor op&ccedil;&atilde;o de verbo modal</p>\r\n'),(2,183,'Relacionar colunas teste','<p>descru&ccedil;&atilde;o</p>\r\n'),(2,184,'Colunas','<p>Combine as colunas com as express&otilde;es idiom&aacute;ticas</p>\r\n'),(2,185,'Atividade 7','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Relacione o pa&iacute;s com a nacionalidade correspondente.</span></p>\r\n'),(2,186,'testando','<p>testando</p>\r\n'),(2,187,'mult esc','<p>mult esc</p>\r\n'),(2,188,'Atividade 8','<p>Podemos identificar o fen&ocirc;meno chamado gaslighting nas seguintes situa&ccedil;&otilde;es. Leia os di&aacute;logos e explique como esse fen&ocirc;meno funciona. O que a pessoa faz ou diz que pode ser considerada uma indica&ccedil;&atilde;o de gaslighting? Em que parte da conversa &eacute; mais clara?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Situation 1:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:633px\">\r\n			<p>Sara works in a company in which there are periodic performance evaluations, with bonus for the best placed professionals. Sara found out that a colleague who held a similar position was making more money and working fewer hours. She decides to talk to her boss.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Mr. Fernandez, I&#39;d like to talk to you about the evaluations. I wonder if I am earning the same amount as Joaquim.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Sara, we know very well that your colleague is competent. This is the reason why you two may have different bonus.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Well, I know he is skilled. However, we have the same position, and I truly believe that I am entitled to get the same bonus as him.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Actually, he&#39;s been more competent than you.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Mr. Fernandez, according to the evaluations, my score is higher than his.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&ldquo;Are you sure? Have you checked the reports correctly?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Yes, I&rsquo;m sure.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;I&#39;m afraid you are being a bit unprofessional. Your colleague has more experience than you and he deserves his bonus.&nbsp;<strong>May I give you some advice, Sara? I really care about your career in this company, so beware of your ambition. There is no point in comparing your bonus to your other colleagues. This is not something that we see with good eyes here</strong>.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Situation 2:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:633px\">\r\n			<p>Luiza and Carlos are students in the Biotechnology undergraduate course.&nbsp; They are in the same group and they have to hand in a report to their professor by the end of the week. Luiza has been working in the report for over a week, and Carlos hasn&#39;t done much and hasn&#39;t returned her calls.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The deadline is getting closer and Luiza decides to talk to him about it. She sends him a message:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/8-1.png\" style=\"height:530px; width:269px\" /><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/8-2.png\" style=\"height:532px; width:335px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/8-3.png\" style=\"height:352px; width:292px\" /></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><u>(</u><a href=\"http://www.fakewhats.com/generator\">http://www.fakewhats.com/generator</a><u>)</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Situation 3:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:633px\">\r\n			<p>Roberta and Jose are speakers in an international conference about Education Health. Each one is going to deliver a lecture in the auditorium. According to the program, Roberta was the first speaker, and Jose was next. However, Jose arrives in the auditorium and starts setting his presentation and slides. Roberta decides to talk to him politely:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Hi! I&#39;m sorry to interrupt you. My name is Roberta, and I am the first speaker. I&#39;m afraid I&#39;ll have to use the computer to organize my presentation.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Oh, nice to meet you Roberta! I&#39;m Jose. Hm... about that. I&#39;m sorry, but I have to go first.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Oh, why is that?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&ldquo;Haven&#39;t anyone told you?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;No... in fact they haven&#39;t. I received an email confirmation from the organizers and the program hasn&#39;t changed. This is weird. What is wrong?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Well, but I&#39;m sure you don&#39;t mind, right? I mean... the order isn&#39;t a big deal.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;I really would like to keep the order. My flight is at 5pm, so I won&#39;t have enough time to get to the airport.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Oh, don&#39;t worry. Is this the only reason?The airport is near here. This is not a problem. Let&#39;s not make a storm in a teacup. &rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;I&#39;m not ma&hellip;&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;You know, the organizers have so many things to do during the conference. Are you sure you want to bother them with that? I would really appreciate if you could help me&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Then, Carla, who is part of the organization, approaches them: &ldquo;Roberta and Jose, is everything ok? Do you need any help?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Oh, everything is fine! I&#39;m just talking to my friend Roberta. I think she is in those days, if you know what I mean! hahaha&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Carla, has the order of presentations changed?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Hm... I don&#39;t think so. Why?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;I&#39;m trying to tell Jose that I am the first speaker.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Well, I can&#39;t believe you still want to go first, Roberta. That is why is so difficult to deal with women, especially those who believe they are superior. They can&rsquo;t negotiate and are often selfish.&quot;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(2,189,'Atividade 9','<p>Considerando essa defini&ccedil;&atilde;o, d&ecirc; uma olhada no desenho animado e escreva&nbsp;(T) True ou&nbsp;(F) False&nbsp;de acordo com as afirma&ccedil;&otilde;es.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/9.jpg\" style=\"height:425px; width:358px\" /></p>\r\n'),(2,190,'Atividade 10: Questão aberta','<p>Quest&atilde;o aberta</p>\r\n'),(2,191,'Atividade 9: Verdadeiro ou falso','<p>Considerando essa defini&ccedil;&atilde;o, d&ecirc; uma olhada no desenho animado e escreva&nbsp;(T) True ou&nbsp;(F) False&nbsp;de acordo com as afirma&ccedil;&otilde;es.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/9.jpg\" style=\"height:425px; width:358px\" /></p>\r\n'),(2,192,'Atividade 4: Diferentes formulações','<p><em>Quais outras formula&ccedil;&otilde;es poder&iacute;amos dizer para completar os bal&otilde;es e manter o tom amig&aacute;vel das conversas originais das personagens? Para cada lacuna, escolha uma das 03 op&ccedil;&otilde;es propostas e fale-a em seu microfone para obter um feedback. &Agrave;s vezes, mais de uma op&ccedil;&atilde;o &eacute; correta.</em></p>\r\n'),(2,193,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 3','<p>Nesta atividade , vamos continuar a praticar a pron&uacute;ncia de fonemas consonantais. Focaremos nos seguintes fonemas e exemplos de palavras:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">/m/ morning&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent\">/n/ nail&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial\">/</span><span style=\"font-family:roboto,sans-serif\">ŋ</span><span style=\"font-family:arial\">/ king</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n'),(2,194,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 4','<p>Nesta atividade , vamos continuar a praticar a pron&uacute;ncia de fonemas consonantais. Focaremos nos seguintes fonemas e exemplos de palavras:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\">/k/ code&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\">/g/ go&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ʧ</span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\">/ chair&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">ʤ</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/ judge</span></p>\r\n'),(2,195,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 5','<p>Nesta atividade , vamos continuar a praticar a pron&uacute;ncia de fonemas consonantais. Focaremos nos seguintes fonemas e exemplos de palavras:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/s/ bus&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/z/ buzz&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ʃ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ share&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">ʒ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/ garage</span></p>\r\n'),(2,196,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 6','<p>Nesta atividade , vamos continuar a praticar a pron&uacute;ncia de fonemas consonantais. Focaremos nos seguintes fonemas e exemplos de palavras:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/h/ hat&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;/l/ love&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/w/ what&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/r/ ring&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/j/ yet&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">ʔ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/ uh-oh</span></p>\r\n'),(2,197,'Atividade 7','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Relacione o pa&iacute;s com a nacionalidade correspondente.</span></p>\r\n'),(2,198,'Atividade 7','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Relacione o pa&iacute;s com a nacionalidade correspondente.</span></p>\r\n'),(2,199,'Atividade 4','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">O tema 2, neste laborat&oacute;rio, intitulado &quot;</span>Academic Encounters&quot;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\"> explora algumas express&otilde;es e entona&ccedil;&otilde;es que s&atilde;o poss&iacute;veis em situa&ccedil;&otilde;es acad&ecirc;micas para concordar ou discordar de proposi&ccedil;&otilde;es ou pedir esclarecimentos, por exemplo, e aborda tamb&eacute;m a quest&atilde;o das identifica&ccedil;&otilde;es sociais e o exerc&iacute;cio do poder na e pela l&iacute;ngua. Nossos personagens no tema 7, &quot;</span>Art for Though<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">t&quot;, tamb&eacute;m est&atilde;o numa situa&ccedil;&atilde;o acad&ecirc;mica: eles s&atilde;o membros de um grupo de pesquisa e est&atilde;o discutindo a rela&ccedil;&atilde;o entre arte, linguagem e produ&ccedil;&atilde;o de sentidos. Enquanto discutem, eles expressam suas opini&otilde;es e se questionam uns aos outros. Nesta atividade, vamos revisar express&otilde;es para concordar, discordar, argumentar, dentre outras. Vamos l&aacute;? Use os n&uacute;meros na Coluna 1 para classificar as frases na Coluna 2.</span></span></p>\r\n'),(2,200,'Prática de pronúncia de fonemas de vogais 3','<p>Nesta atividade, vamos continuar a realizar as repeti&ccedil;&otilde;es vogais. Vamos l&aacute;?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɝ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ bird&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">ɚ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/ letter</span></span></p>\r\n'),(2,201,'Prática de pronúncia de fonemas de vogais 4','<p>Nesta atividade, vamos continuar a realizar as repeti&ccedil;&otilde;es vogais. Vamos l&aacute;?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/e</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɪ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ day&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/a</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɪ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ die&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɔɪ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ joint&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/a</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ʊ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ now&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ou/ coat</span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(2,202,'Atividade 11','<p>Ou&ccedil;a as seguintes palavras e escolha os fonemas que ouvir:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<body id=\"cke_pastebin\" style=\"position: absolute; top: -10px; width: 1px; height: 180px; overflow: hidden; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; left: -1000px;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:rgb(248, 249, 250); color:rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family:arial,sans-serif; font-size:28px; white-space:pre-wrap\">Ou&ccedil;a as seguintes palavras e escolha os fonemas que ouvir nas primeiras consoantes:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</body>\r\n'),(2,203,'teste','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">teste</span></p>\r\n'),(2,204,'Atividade 3: Combine imagem e palavra','<p>Observe a imagem e escolha a op&ccedil;&atilde;o correspondente.</p>\r\n'),(3,55,'Activity 1: Listening and repetition','<p><em>How about practicing your listening and speaking skills? Use the play, pause and record buttons to listen to the dialogues and record your voice. Then, compare your recordings to the lines of the characters. You can record and listen to the audio files as many times as you want.</em></p>\r\n'),(3,58,'Activity 2: Spelling','<p><em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Knowing how to spell always helps to solve doubts like these. The English alphabet is formed by 26 letters. None of them has diacritics (like the cedilha of the Portuguese </span>&ccedil;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">, for example). Shall we review the letters?</span></em></p>\r\n'),(3,61,'Activity 3: Title and meaning','<p><em>The title of this unit is I see you. After having heard the story and performed the previous activities, why do you think this unit has this title? Please record an audio file with your answer. </em></p>\r\n'),(3,63,'Activity 1: Listening and repetition','<p><em>Listening and repetition</em></p>\r\n'),(3,73,'Activity 2: Enunciative (im)possibilities','<div>\r\n<p>A professora tenta contornar a situa&ccedil;&atilde;o um pouco embara&ccedil;osa causada pelo riso da colega, encorajando Priscila a continuar seu racioc&iacute;nio (<em>Well, but no problems&hellip; go on. What do you think this &lsquo;course&rsquo; is about?</em>). Todavia, o di&aacute;logo poderia ter sido um pouco diferente. A professora, e n&atilde;o uma colega, poderia ter corrigido Priscila.&nbsp; Imaginemos a seguinte situa&ccedil;&atilde;o:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Priscila:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m Priscila... I don&rsquo;t know this &lsquo;curse&rsquo;&hellip; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Professora:&nbsp;&nbsp; Oh, course not curse, ok?</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Priscila:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What? I said wrong?</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Professora: Yes, you said &lsquo;curse&rsquo; but the word is &lsquo;course&rsquo;. Curse is a completely different thing&hellip;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1) Como voc&ecirc; se sentiria no lugar de Priscila?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2) Como voc&ecirc; entende o posicionamento da professora?​</strong></p>\r\n</div>\r\n'),(3,74,'Activity 3: What\'s intelligibility?','<div>\r\n<p>Observe a fala de Priscila no Quadro 7 (<em>ok&hellip; right. I can&rsquo;t speak&hellip; I understand more and read... Well&hellip; this course about methodology?</em>). Apesar de se mostrar com algumas inconsist&ecirc;ncias gramaticais, pode-se compreend&ecirc;-la no contexto em que &eacute; enunciada. Isso nos remete &agrave; discuss&atilde;o sobre o conceito de <strong>inteligibilidade</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nesse &aacute;udio 1, a partir de uma situa&ccedil;&atilde;o relativamente simples, aponta para as rela&ccedil;&otilde;es de poder que constituem a tomada da palavra, fazendo com que esta jamais seja um ato neutro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ao dizer <em>I&rsquo;d like to know how we can have access to the texts </em>(&aacute;udio 2)<em>, </em>Juliana n&atilde;o est&aacute; interessada em uma mera informa&ccedil;&atilde;o. O que est&aacute; aqui em jogo, mais do que a referencialidade da linguagem, &eacute; a possibilidade, para os falantes, de produzirem certos dizeres e assumirem lugares (social, discursivo) perante o outro. Diante da sugest&atilde;o da professora para que os alunos adquirissem os livros a serem estudados na disciplina, Juliana se posiciona contrariando a expectativa da docente (<em>But do you know if they are available in the library? I guess they&rsquo;re a little bit expensive</em>) (&aacute;udio 3) e, confrontando, de certa forma, uma voz institucional.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n'),(3,75,'Activity 1: Listening and Repeat','<p>Listening and Repeat</p>\r\n'),(3,76,'Activity 2: Idiomatic expressions','<p>Look some idiomatic expressions that can be used to replace the expressions used by the characters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Felicity: Good idea,&nbsp;<strong>I&rsquo;m starving</strong>!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I could eat a horse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I could murder a (burger /&nbsp;steak&nbsp;/ pizza) right now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so ravenous I could eat a horse!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">4)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so starved I could eat a horse!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">5)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m famished. I could murder a burger!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">6)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so hungry I could murder a whole pizza right now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ethan: <strong>Are you crazy</strong>? Oh God!&nbsp;<strong>You eat a lot</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have you ever gone bananas? You eat like a horse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have you ever gone bananas? You eat like a pig.</p>\r\n'),(3,77,'Activity 3: Modal Verbs Practice','<p>Check the best sense for these modal verbs.</p>\r\n'),(3,78,'Activity 3: The food song','<p>Look at the pictures with foods and stuffs related to food that can be found in the song: <strong>The Food Song</strong> by Barbra Lica.</p>\r\n'),(3,79,'Activity 4: The food song (lyric and video)','<p>The Food Song<br />\r\nBy Barbra Lica</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nHey, I had a bad day,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And I wondered how it <strong>TASTES</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I ATE...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And then I served myself a second <strong>PLATE</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad week,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And I wonder if it&#39;s <strong>SWEET</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I&#39;ll <strong>EAT</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Cause I deserve to give myself a treat...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sadness tastes like <strong>FRENCH FRIES</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And anger tastes like <strong>WINE</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They&#39;re only <strong>GRAPES </strong>but give them time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad night,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I wrapped it up in <strong>PIE</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And let it <strong>BAKE</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So all my feelings taste like <strong>TENDERFLAKE</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh joy, my mum just called.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And she&#39;s appalled because my dad don&#39;t want to <strong>SPOON</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ll take that <strong>SPOON</strong>, and put some <strong>ICE-CREAM </strong>on my afternoon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But guilty tastes like <strong>NOODLES</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lonely tastes like <strong>BREAD</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But <strong>TOAST </strong>can make a royal friend, hmmm!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yup! Everything is wonderful...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yeah! So walk it off, walk it off,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Circle the block,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <strong>COOKIES </strong>and <strong>CREAM</strong> are starting to talk to me...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m just crazy...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But crazy tastes so good,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crazy tastes so nice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crazy tastes like never-have-to-go outside.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here we go now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day so I ate it all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED</strong>.</p>\r\n'),(3,80,'Activity 5: The food song (Karaoke)','<p>Let&#39;s sing! Listen and repeat!</p>\r\n'),(3,81,'Activity 7: Match the sentences','<p>Match the idiomatic expression with its meaning.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Your eyes are bigger than your stomach</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Have you ever gone bananas?</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Compare apples to oranges</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Eat like a horse</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Cry over spilled milk</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Piece of cake</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Bring home the bacon</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Have egg on one&rsquo;s face</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) I ate like a pig</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) A rotten apple</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) A smart cookie</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) As busy as popcorn on a skillet</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Back to the salt mines</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Big cheese</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Bite the hand that feeds one</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) I&rsquo;m cheesed off</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Couch potato</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) As cool as a cucumber</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Fruits of one&rsquo;s labor</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Hot potato</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n'),(3,83,'Activity 6: Reading and Comprehension','<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">Read and answer the questions!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Our Moods, Our Foods</strong></span><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:18px\">The messy relationship between how we feel and what we eat</span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"c-article-meta\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; -webkit-box-align: baseline; align-items: baseline; display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<address>\r\n<address><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><a class=\"c-byline__link\" href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/author/julie-beck/\" style=\"color: rgb(231, 19, 26); background-color: transparent; text-decoration-line: none; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit;\">JULIE BECK</a>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:10px\">MARCH 6, 2014</span></address>\r\n</address>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0)\">Eating a meal, any meal, reliably makes an animal, any animal, calmer and more lethargic. This means humans, too. Hunger makes animals alert and irritable, which explains why couples always fight about where to eat dinner. This emotional response encourages the animals to find food.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">But all this is only in the broadest, most primal &ldquo;eating = good, not eating = bad&rdquo; way. The details of the relationship between foods and moods end up being a little contradictory and a lot complicated.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">What we tend to think of as &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a specific kind of eating and a specific kind of emotion&mdash;eating sugary, fatty, carb-y, unhealthy foods as a coping mechanism for feeling upset. &nbsp;In reality, &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a much broader term.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We eat for a variety of different emotions and we eat in a variety of different circumstances which are in turn connected with emotions,&rdquo; Meryl Gardner, a marketing professor at the University of Delaware, says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner was the lead author on a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057740814000060\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">new study</a>&nbsp;published in the&nbsp;<em>Journal of Consumer Psychology,&nbsp;</em>which looked at food choice and mood, adding to a fairly extensive body of research that already exists on the interplay between moods and foods.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">There seems to be a clear, fairly consistent connection between negative emotions and unhealthy foods, though there are individual variations for what&nbsp;<em>kind</em>&nbsp;of snack people want. In a bad mood, people&rsquo;s hands tend to float to the cookie jar, the candy bag, the snack drawer. What&rsquo;s less clear is what foods we&rsquo;re drawn to in a positive mood.</span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">What we tend to think of as &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a specific kind of eating and a specific kind of emotion&mdash;eating sugary, fatty, carb-y, unhealthy foods as a coping mechanism for feeling upset. &nbsp;In reality, &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a much broader term.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We eat for a variety of different emotions and we eat in a variety of different circumstances which are in turn connected with emotions,&rdquo; Meryl Gardner, a marketing professor at the University of Delaware, says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner was the lead author on a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057740814000060\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">new study</a>&nbsp;published in the&nbsp;<em>Journal of Consumer Psychology,&nbsp;</em>which looked at food choice and mood, adding to a fairly extensive body of research that already exists on the interplay between moods and foods.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">There seems to be a clear, fairly consistent connection between negative emotions and unhealthy foods, though there are individual variations for what&nbsp;<em>kind</em>&nbsp;of snack people want. In a bad mood, people&rsquo;s hands tend to float to the cookie jar, the candy bag, the snack drawer. What&rsquo;s less clear is what foods we&rsquo;re drawn to in a positive mood.</span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Some studies say we still want treats. A&nbsp;<a href=\"http://psycnet.apa.org/?&amp;fa=main.doiLanding&amp;doi=10.1037/0021-843X.101.2.348\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">1992 study</a>&nbsp;and a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ac.els-cdn.com/S019566630290499X/1-s2.0-S019566630290499X-main.pdf?_tid=edbdeba6-a479-11e3-a8a5-00000aacb360&amp;acdnat=1394033113_c88ed7a56c3e1767060124c3588f4ec2\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">2002 study</a>&nbsp;(one on women, one on men) found that joy led to increased consumption of indulgent foods. A 2013 study in&nbsp;<em>Appetite</em>&nbsp;titled &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S019566631300130X\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">Happy Eating: The underestimated role of overeating in a positive mood</a>&rdquo; points out the potential for increased consumption (in this case of chips and chocolate) when we&rsquo;re feeling good.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Other research says just the opposite&mdash;that we&rsquo;re more likely to eschew the sugar/carb rush when happy. In 2010,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.1086/655665?uid=3739256&amp;uid=2&amp;uid=4&amp;sid=21103592979347\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">researchers found</a>&nbsp;that people in a positive mood were more likely to choose grapes over chocolate than those in a neutral mood.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.1086/597159?uid=3739256&amp;uid=2&amp;uid=4&amp;sid=21103592979347\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">Another study</a>&nbsp;offers a qualification, finding that people would choose healthy foods if they felt like their good mood was going to stick around; if not, they might eat more indulgent foods, to keep the good vibes going.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner&rsquo;s study also found a connection between negative moods and unhealthy foods, and positive moods and healthy foods, but she and her team introduced the element of time into the equation as well. They had participants think about either the present or the future (by describing their current residence, or a possible future residence). They found that regardless of mood, long-term, future-focused thinking led to healthier choices.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;When you&rsquo;re in a good mood, you take a longer-term perspective,&rdquo; Gardner says. &ldquo;You see the forest, not the trees... When you&rsquo;re focused on the near term, when you&rsquo;re looking at what&rsquo;s in front of your nose, you respond with what&rsquo;s going to give you quick pleasure. And that&rsquo;s triggered very much by bad moods. But we can fight that.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Dr. Leigh Gibson, a psychology professor at the University of Roehampton in London, disagrees, though he says he finds those results interesting. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not sure that&rsquo;s the way people normally go about their daily eating,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;For habitual behaviors like eating, there tends to be an intention-behavior gap. We have all these wonderful intentions, but when it comes down to it, we&rsquo;re exposed to energy-dense foods when we find ourselves hungry.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">It does seem unlikely that most of us would take the time to describe our future homes to ourselves before deciding on pizza or a salad for lunch. And as previously noted, there is little consensus on what we typically crave when we&rsquo;re happy.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Part of the reason why it seems our moods rarely drive us toward healthy foods, Gibson says, is that for much of human history, energy-dense foods, or what we now consider comfort foods, were the ideal thing to eat.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We didn&rsquo;t evolve as homo sapiens by eating healthy, because all we had to do was reproduce and survive until our mid-20&rsquo;s,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;We were quite happily sucking the marrow out of bones. We were just getting energy, protein, the basic nutrients we needed, but we didn&rsquo;t have to live too long. Healthy eating is a modern, cultural thing that we now need, because we&rsquo;re living so long&hellip; You could almost say the default is comfort eating.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">We&rsquo;re not constantly shoveling mashed potatoes into our mouths (at least not most of the time), so of course this doesn&rsquo;t mean that humans don&rsquo;t ever choose healthy foods, just that when we do, it might not be in response to our emotions.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Another reason for this lack of consensus is that there are a variety of moods that can fit under the &ldquo;positive&rdquo; umbrella&mdash;feeling excited is very different from feeling content, and those emotions could lead to similarly divergent food choices.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">For example, Gardner says we tend to go for special, often unhealthy, foods on celebratory occasions, like birthdays or Thanksgiving.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;You eat the birthday cake, you may go out in the evening and eat more appetizers and drink more cocktails than you intended, and it&rsquo;s all part of the specialness of the occasion,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;And we&rsquo;ve all learned to celebrate with food. It&rsquo;s part of so many different cultures.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Carol Landau&mdash;a clinical professor of psychiatry, human behavior, and medicine at Brown University&mdash;points out that some comfort eaters turn everything into a celebration, rewarding themselves with food not just for special occasions, but for everyday accomplishments as well.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Food is such an important part of culture,&rdquo; Landau says. &ldquo;I think we&rsquo;re asking people to do a lot [by asking them] to avoid comfort eating.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gibson says this sort of celebratory eating seems to be more prevalent for men than women. There&rsquo;s also some evidence that the foods men and women turn to for comfort are different&mdash;men often get more comfort from savory foods and &ldquo;general meal-type foods,&rdquo; Gibson says, as opposed to snacks. Gardner says she has also found men to be more drawn to salty foods.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Sweet foods, however, seem to be a universal crowd-pleaser.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Sweetness is such a powerful stimulus,&rdquo; Gibson says. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re born initially liking sweetness. It probably helps [that babies] have an appetite for breast milk and so on.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">This may well be why the go-to image of comfort eating in culture is someone crying into a pint of Ben &amp; Jerry&rsquo;s, and why so many studies on mood and food choice include chocolate as one of the unhealthy options.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;If one can characterize [comfort] foods in any simple way, it would be that they&rsquo;re typically energy-dense,&rdquo; Gibson says. &ldquo;Therefore they&rsquo;re probably high fat, and they might be sweet as well. The perfect comfort food might be chocolate.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">But as we all know, the positive effects of eating sweets are short-lived. Whether it&rsquo;s a crash that comes after a sugar high, or just a feeling of guilt after eating more cookies than you planned, treats are not a ticket to long-term happiness.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">So in the chicken-or-the-egg problem of food and mood, do the moods hatch the foods, or do the foods hatch the moods? Studies disagree&mdash;the relationship seems to go both ways. A couple recent studies suggest that the foods come first.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">In a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S019566631100643X\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">study published in 2012</a>, Penn State psychology professor Dr. Helen Hendy had 44 undergraduate students keep week-long diaries of how they felt and what they ate. She analyzed the results in terms of four things the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommend we should limit to improve physical health: calories, carbohydrates, saturated fat, and sodium. Following those recommendations, Hendy found, seemed to have benefits for improving moods as well.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">She found that the link between foods and moods played out over a period of two days&mdash;what you ate on day one was linked to how you felt on day three, etc. As usual, the correlation was more consistent with negative moods: &ldquo;Consumption of calories, saturated fat, and sodium was significantly associated with increased negative mood two days later,&rdquo; the study reads.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Some of my research leads me to change my habits, and this one has,&rdquo; Hendy says. &ldquo;I have a big meeting [in two days], so today I&rsquo;m going to watch my calories, my sodium, and my saturated fat, so I can hopefully have a chance to be in a good mood.&rdquo;</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">A similar study,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/bjhp.12021/abstract\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">published in the&nbsp;<em>British Journal of Health Psychology</em></a>&nbsp;in 2013, had 281 undergrads keep a 21-day diary, and did find a correlation between eating fruits and vegetables one day and being in a positive mood the next day. The association with eating fruit was stronger for men, but both men and women benefitted from eating veggies. Participants&rsquo; BMI did not affect the association.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">The exact reasons why healthy eating might make you happy are unclear, but Gibson posits that if you intend to eat healthily, and you follow through, that could put you in a good mood. &ldquo;Achieving goals is part and parcel of emotional experience,&rdquo; he says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Both eating and emotion are such regular, consistent parts of our lives that it&rsquo;s inevitable they would get tangled up together. Unfortunately, though research has illuminated some interesting possibilities as to how they relate to one another, the knot is still very much intact and it&rsquo;s hard to see where one ends and the other begins.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;There&rsquo;s not a very neat story there,&rdquo; Gibson says. Regardless, there&rsquo;s a bit more to it than just feeling sad and therefore reaching for a spoon and some ice cream, or whatever your preferred unhealthy snack is. It seems entirely possible that all eating is, in fact, emotional eating.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\"><strong>Source</strong>:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/our-moods-our-foods/284238/\">https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/our-moods-our-foods/284238/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">1)&nbsp; According to the text what are the emotions linked to the necessity of eating?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp; In the song,&nbsp;<strong>The Food Song</strong>, what are the reasons that lead the protagonist to eat?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">3)&nbsp;&nbsp; And you, what are the emotions that affect your diet? Explain: What are your food choices in different situations?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4)&nbsp;&nbsp; Are you an emotional eater? &nbsp;Why?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(3,84,'Activity 1: Parts of the body','<p>Look at the parts of the body.</p>\r\n'),(3,85,'Activity 2: Complete with the parts of the body','<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/BODY%201.JPG\" style=\"height:523px; width:594px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/HEAD%202.JPG\" style=\"height:520px; width:606px\" /></p>\r\n'),(3,86,'Activity 3: Let’s practice!','<p>Type the correct answer into the blanks: must - can&#39;t - might</p>\r\n'),(3,87,'Activity 4: About racism','<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">One of the social issues addressed by the story is that of racism. As it is well known, racism consists in the belief of a supposed supremacy of one race over another. Although there are various campaigns to combat racism in different parts of the world, this is a practice that still manifests itself in different ways in our daily lives. Could you tell us how these practices materialize in the story presented? Why does it happen?</p>\r\n'),(3,88,'Activity 5: Read the text','<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">As mentioned before, racist practices manifest themselves in different ways, one of which is in the strangeness of certain languages and / or linguistic practices. In the English language, some of their speakers suffer from racism simply because they speak differently from what is considered standard English. Have you ever heard about African English? How Let&rsquo;s learn a little about this variant?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\"><strong>Read the text and answer the following questions.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">What is Ebonics (African American English)?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:90pt\">By John R. Rickford</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">At its most literal level, Ebonics simply means &#39;black speech&#39; (a blend of the words ebony &#39;black&#39; and phonics &#39;sounds&#39;). The term was created in 1973 by a group of black scholars who disliked the negative connotations of terms like &#39;Nonstandard Negro English&#39; that had been coined in the 1960s when the first modern large-scale linguistic studies of African American speech-communities began. However, the term Ebonics never caught on among linguists, much less among the general public. That all changed with the &#39;Ebonics&#39; controversy of December 1996 when the Oakland (CA) School Board recognized it as the &#39;primary&#39; language of its majority African American students and resolved to take it into account in teaching them standard or academic English.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">1____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">Ebonics pronunciation includes features like the omission of the final consonant in words like &#39;past&#39; (pas&#39; ) and &#39;hand&#39; (han&#39;), the pronunciation of the th in &#39;bath&#39; as t (bat) or f (baf), and the pronunciation of the vowel in words like &#39;my&#39; and &#39;ride&#39; as a long ah (mah, rahd). Some of these occur in vernacular white English, too, especially in the South, but in general they occur more frequently in Ebonics. Some Ebonics pronunciations are more unique, for instance, dropping b, d, or g at the beginning of auxiliary verbs like &#39;don&#39;t&#39; and &#39;gonna&#39;, yielding Ah &#39;on know for &quot;I don&#39;t know&quot; and ama do it for &quot;I&#39;m going to do it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">2____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">These distinctive Ebonics pronunciations are all systematic, the result of regular rules and restrictions; they are not random &#39;error&#39;--and this is equally true of Ebonics grammar. For instance, Ebonics speakers regularly produce sentences without present tense is and are, as in &quot;John trippin&quot; or &quot;They allright&quot;. But they don&#39;t omit present tense am. Instead of the ungrammatical *&quot;Ah walkin&quot;, Ebonics speakers would say *&quot;Ahm walkin.&quot; Likewise, they do not omit is and are if they come at the end of a sentence--&quot;That&#39;s what he/they&quot; is ungrammatical. Many members of the public seem to have heard, too, that Ebonics speakers use an &#39;invariant&#39; be in their speech (as in &quot;They be goin to school every day&quot;); however, this be is not simply equivalent to is or are. Invariant be refers to actions that occur regularly or habitually rather than on just one occasion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">3____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">That depends on whom you ask. Black writers from Paul Laurence Dunbar to Zora Neale Hurston to August Wilson have made extensive use of it in their work, and some, like James Baldwin (&quot;this passion, this skill, ... this incredible music.&quot;), Toni Morrison, and June Jordan have praised it explicitly. Black preachers and comedians and singers, especially rappers, also use it for dramatic or realistic effect. But many other people, black and white, regard it as a sign of limited education or sophistication, as a legacy of slavery or an impediment to socioeconomic mobility. Some deny its existence (like the black Chicagoan whose words &quot;Ain&#39;t nobody here talkin&#39; no Ebonics&quot; belied his claim). Others deprecate it (like Maya Angelou, who found the Oakland School Board&#39;s 1996 Ebonics resolutions &quot;very threatening&quot; although she uses Ebonics herself in her poems, e.g. &quot;The Pusher&quot;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">4____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">On this point, linguists are quite divided. Some emphasize its English origins, pointing to the fact that most of the vocabulary of Ebonics is from English and that much of its pronunciation (e.g. pronouncing final th as f) and grammar (e.g. double negatives, &quot;I don&#39;t want none&quot;) could have come from the nonstandard dialects of English indentured servants and other workers with whom African slaves interacted. Others emphasize Ebonics&#39; African origins, noting that West African languages often lack th sounds and final consonant clusters (e.g. past), and that replacing or simplifying these occurs both in US Ebonics and in West African English varieties spoken in Nigeria and Ghana.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">(Adapted from: https://www.linguisticsociety.org/content/what-ebonics-african-american-english )</p>\r\n'),(3,89,'Atividade 1: Listening and repetition','<p>Listening and repetition</p>\r\n'),(3,91,'Activity 2 - Deliberation','<p>You&rsquo;ve probably noticed that the use of &ldquo;she&rdquo; referring to the actor&rsquo;s partner caused embarrassment to the actor, whose partner is a man, not a woman. So the question is: which pronoun &ndash; &ldquo;he&rdquo;, &ldquo;she&rdquo; or &ldquo;they&rdquo; &ndash; should be used with reference to words that can refer to both genders, like &ldquo;partner&rdquo;, &ldquo;student&rdquo;, &ldquo;teacher&rdquo;, &ldquo;colleague&rdquo;, &ldquo;author&rdquo;, &ldquo;doctor&rdquo;, &ldquo;person&rdquo;, among so many others? In other words, how can gender bias be avoided? For many years, people tended to use &ldquo;he&rdquo; (and &ldquo;him&rdquo;, &ldquo;his&rdquo;, &ldquo;himself&rdquo;) to refer to such words, for example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since <em>he</em> may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in <em>his</em> findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, this is considered to be sexist and instead, therefore some people use &ldquo;he or she&rdquo;:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since <em>he or she</em> may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in <em>his or her</em> findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem is that frequent repetition of &ldquo;he or she&rdquo; slows down reading and writing. Therefore, people may choose to use third person plural pronouns: &ldquo;they&rdquo;, &ldquo;them&rdquo;, &ldquo;their&rdquo;, &ldquo;theirs&rdquo; and &ldquo;themselves&rdquo; (or &ldquo;themself&rdquo; in informal contexts). Although the use of plural pronouns to refer back to a singular subject may seem wrong, it&rsquo;s increasingly common in both written and spoken English:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since <em>they</em> may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in <em>their</em> findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Can you think of other gender-neutral words? Do you believe using gender-neutral words and pronouns can help avoid sexist behaviour in general? Why (not)? In the following article, published by &ldquo;The Guardian&rdquo;, the author suggests that&nbsp; gender is a &ldquo;primary way of signifying relationships of power&rdquo;. Do you agree?&nbsp; Read the article by clicking on:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/may/05/they-the-singular-pronoun-that-could-solve-sexism-in-english\">www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/may/05/they-the-singular-pronoun-that-could-solve-sexism-in-english</a></p>\r\n'),(3,92,'Activity 3','<p>When the TV presenter asked the actor how he got the role, he answered: &ldquo;One day my agent just&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\"><strong>called&nbsp;</strong></span>me to say that they&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\"><strong>were staging</strong></span>&nbsp;an adaptation of Jessica Richmond&rsquo;s novel&rdquo;. Can you tell the difference between the verb tenses underlined above?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Were staging&rdquo; (Past Continuous) suggests something that was happening around a particular point in the past, whereas &ldquo;called&rdquo; (Past Simple) expresses the idea of a short action.&nbsp; These tenses are often used together, as in: &ldquo;I played Stanley in &ldquo;A streetcar named Desire&rdquo; two years ago, and&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\"><strong>was preparing</strong></span>&nbsp;for my first movie role when the audition&nbsp;<strong><span class=\"marker\">came up</span></strong>.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In cases like this, the&nbsp;Past Continuous&nbsp;describes a longer, background action and the&nbsp;Past Simple&nbsp;describes the events.</p>\r\n'),(3,93,'Activity 4','<p>Bearing in mind what you learned in Activities 3 and 4, say what was happening in each of the pictures below:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/cellular-education-classroom-159844.jpeg\" style=\"height:387px; width:580px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ex: The teacher was writing on the board while the student was texting</p>\r\n'),(3,94,'Activity 5','<p>Can you guess what the following underlined expressions mean?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I was preparing for my first movie role when the audition&nbsp;<u>came up</u>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I think women have to&nbsp;<u>stand up for</u>&nbsp;their rights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The expressions underlined are known as phrasal verbs. Phrasal verbs are combinations of verbs with prepositions (ex: for), adverbs (ex: up) or both (ex: up for) that function as verbs which have meanings different from the meaning of the words considered separately. In the first case, &ldquo;came up&rdquo; means &ldquo;became available&rdquo;, and in the second, &ldquo;stand up for&rdquo; means &ldquo;defend&rdquo;. Here are a few other phrasal verbs you may know:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Can you&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/turn_1\">turn</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<u>up</u>&nbsp;the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/volume\">air</a>&nbsp;conditioner a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/bit_1\">bit</a>?&nbsp; (to increase the amount of sound, heat or light by pressing a button)</li>\r\n	<li>Will you&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/turn_1\">turn</a>&nbsp;the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/music\">music</a>&nbsp;<u>down</u>&nbsp;a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/bit_1\">bit</a>? (to reduce the amount of sound, heat or light by pressing a button)</li>\r\n	<li>Why did you&nbsp;<u>turn down</u>&nbsp;that fantastic offer? (to not accept an offer or request)</li>\r\n	<li>Frank is the most sociable person I know &ndash; he&nbsp;<u>gets on</u>&nbsp;with everyone (to have a good relationship with someone)</li>\r\n	<li>How do politicians&nbsp;<u>get away with</u>&nbsp;corruption? (to manage to do something bad without being punished or&nbsp;criticised&nbsp;for it)</li>\r\n	<li>Chris lost five kilos since she&nbsp;<u>took up</u>&nbsp;jogging. (to start doing something as a habit, job or interest)</li>\r\n	<li>I can&rsquo;t&nbsp;<u>take on</u>&nbsp;any more work right now. (to accept work or responsibility)</li>\r\n	<li>Sam started his business five years ago but it only&nbsp;<u>took off</u>&nbsp;last year. (to start to be successful or popular)</li>\r\n	<li>I&nbsp;<u>took to</u>&nbsp;Sarah immediately.(to begin to like someone or something)</li>\r\n	<li>We were terribly worried but t<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/thing\">hings</a>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/work_1\">worked</a><u>&nbsp;out</u>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/pretty_1\">pretty</a>&nbsp;well in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/end_1\">end</a>. (to be&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/successful\">successful</a>, or to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/end_1\">end</a>&nbsp;in a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/particular_1\">particular</a>&nbsp;way)</li>\r\n	<li>Children often&nbsp;<u>look up to</u>&nbsp;Brazilian footballers. (to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/admire\">admire</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/respect_1\">respect</a>&nbsp;someone)</li>\r\n	<li>You shouldn&rsquo;t&nbsp;<u>look down on</u>&nbsp;people who don&rsquo;t earn as much as you do. (to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/think_1\">think</a>&nbsp;that you are&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/better_1\">better</a>&nbsp;or more&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/important\">important</a>&nbsp;than someone else, or to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/think_1\">think</a>&nbsp;that something is not&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/good_1\">good</a>&nbsp;enough for you)</li>\r\n	<li>At&nbsp;first&nbsp;I didn&rsquo;t&nbsp;<u>catch on</u>&nbsp;what his real intentions were. (to understand)</li>\r\n	<li>I had to&nbsp;<u>make up</u>&nbsp;an excuse about losing my key. (to invent a story, or explanation for something, in order to avoid being punished for something)</li>\r\n	<li>The children&nbsp;<u>made off</u>&nbsp;when they heard their parents arrive. (to leave quickly, especially after doing something wrong)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The list of phrasal verbs in English is really long, and the same phrasal verb may have several meanings (as is the case of &ldquo;turn down&rdquo;, for example, as well as most of the other phrasal verbs above). The best way of learning them is by paying attention to the contexts in which they are used. In the next activity you&rsquo;ll have a chance to practice some of them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(3,103,'Activity 1','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12px\"><em>Most times, dictionary definitions are oversimplified and incomplete. Look at the definition of &ldquo;multiculturalism&rdquo; presented by Macmillan Dictionary, and an expanded and more complete explanation of the term.</em></span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Macmillan dictionary:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">multiculturalism - the belief and practice of giving equal importance to each of the different cultures in a society</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Expanded definition:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">The term &lsquo;multiculturalism&rsquo; is sometimes used to describe a condition of society; more precisely, it is used to describe a society where a variety of different cultures coexist. Many countries in the world are culturally diverse. Canada is just one example, including a variety of cultures such as English Canadians, Quebecois, Native Americans, Amish, Hutterites and Chinese immigrants. (...) There are a variety of ways whereby societies can be diverse, for example, culture can come in many forms (Gurr, 1993, p. 3). (...) Religious diversity is a widespread phenomenon in many countries. India can be given as an example of a country which is religiously diverse, including citizens who are Sikhs, Hindus, Buddhists, among other religious groups. (...) Linguistic diversity is also widespread. In the 21st century, there are more than 200 countries in the world and around 6000 spoken languages (Laitin, 2007). Linguistic diversity usually results from two kinds of groups. (...) The second kind of groups that are a cause of linguistic diversity are national minorities. National minorities are groups that have either settled in the country for a long time, but do not share the same language with the majority. (...) A third kind of group diversity can result from distinct territory location. This territory location does not necessarily mean that members of distinct cultures are, in fact, different. That is, it is not necessary that habits, traditions, customs, and so forth are significantly different. However, these distinct groups identify themselves as different from others because of the specific geographical area in which they are located. (...) The fourth kind of group diversity is race. Races are groups whose physical characteristics are imbued with social significance. In other words, race is a socially constructed concept in the sense that it is the result of individuals giving social significance to a set of characteristics they consider that stand out in a person&#39;s physical appearance, such as skin color, eye color, hair color, bone/jaw structure and so forth. However, the mere existence of different physical characteristics does not mean that there is a multicultural environment/society. (...) That is, racial cultural diversity is not simply the existence of different physical characteristics. Rather, these different physical characteristics must entail a sense of common identity which, in turn, are socially perceived as something that differentiates the members of that group to others. (...) The social significance given to these physical differences are sufficient for members of both groups, broadly speaking, to identify as members of one group or the other, and subsequently oppose to each other. (</span><a href=\"https://www.iep.utm.edu/multicul/#H2\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial\">https://www.iep.utm.edu/multicul/#H2</span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">)&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12px\"><em>Now, write expanded definitions for the following dictionary definitions:</em></span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n'),(3,104,'Activity 2','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><em>In the video, Helena and Caetano talk about salad bowl saying that &quot;Our family is such a salad bowl we can practically cover the whole world with it</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">.</span><em>&quot;. Considering the context of their family, what do you understand by that expression. Do you think it is similar or different from the concept of melting pot?</em></span></p>\r\n'),(3,120,'Activity 4: Wrapping it up!','<p>As situa&ccedil;&otilde;es apresentadas nos audios 1, 2 e 3 nos fazem pensar em (im)possibilidades enunciativas, ou seja, no fato de que nem tudo pode ser dito &ndash; seja em l&iacute;ngua materna ou estrangeira. E tal impossibilidade deve-se n&atilde;o apenas por uma suposta falta de profici&ecirc;ncia do falante, mas a fatores que remetem &agrave; rela&ccedil;&atilde;o da l&iacute;ngua com a hist&oacute;ria, dos sentidos com os quais os sujeitos se identificam, das condi&ccedil;&otilde;es de produ&ccedil;&atilde;o da enuncia&ccedil;&atilde;o (que s&atilde;o &uacute;nicas e irrepet&iacute;veis), das imagens que o interlocutor tem de si e do(s) outro(s). Ademais, h&aacute; de se considerar que essas (im)possibilidades dizem respeito &agrave; natureza sempre tensa e conflitiva da tomada significante da palavra, j&aacute; que, ao significar o mundo, nos significamos &lsquo;no&rsquo; mundo. Ou seja, ao dizer (d)o outro, digo de mim, me posiciono em rela&ccedil;&atilde;o ao outro e o posiciono em rela&ccedil;&atilde;o a mim.</p>\r\n'),(3,121,'Activity 6: Modals of deduction','<p>We use modal verbs to say how sure we are about something.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>must </strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use must when we feel sure that something is true because there&rsquo;s very strong evidence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He must live near here because he comes to work on foot. We don&rsquo;t know where he lives but we&rsquo;re sure it&rsquo;s not far away.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Come inside and get warm &ndash; you must be freezing out there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&rsquo;re a zookeeper? That must be very interesting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notice that must is followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>might, may, could</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use might, may or could to say that we think something is possible but we&rsquo;re not sure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Did you hear that? I think there might be a burglar downstairs. She&rsquo;s not sure there&rsquo;s a burglar but she thinks it&rsquo;s possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ll try to get there early but we may arrive late if there&rsquo;s a lot of traffic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t put it up there. It could fall off and hit someone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Might, may and could are also followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>can&rsquo;t</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use can&rsquo;t when we feel sure something is not true.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It can&rsquo;t be a burglar. All the doors and windows are locked. He doesn&rsquo;t know it&rsquo;s not a burglar but he feels sure it&rsquo;s not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It can&rsquo;t be far away now. We&rsquo;ve been driving for hours. Where&rsquo;s the map?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Really? He has to work on Christmas Day? He can&rsquo;t feel very happy about that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like the other verbs, can&rsquo;t is followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n'),(3,122,'Activity 7: Think about','<p>Using your own words, could you tell us what Ebonics is?</p>\r\n'),(3,135,'Pronunciation practice: vowel phonemes','<p>In this activity, we invite you to watch and repeat the videos of some&nbsp;vowel phonemes and example words. Shall we?</p>\r\n'),(3,140,'Activity 2: Different linguistic formulations','<p><em>What other formulations could we say to complete the speech balloons and maintain the friendly tone of the characters&#39; original conversations? For each blank, choose one of the 03 options proposed and speak into your microphone for feedback. Sometimes more than one option is correct.</em></p>\r\n'),(3,142,'Activity 3','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Code switching is a linguistic phenomenon in which people change the way the speak to a more formal or informal mode of speech. It is also a phenomenon in which people use two or more languages to communicate with each other.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\">As we&rsquo;ve seen in the video, Helena and Caetano live in a translingualistic environment because they use three languages, sometimes in one sentence, to speak to one another.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Write a text explaining what you understand as translingualistic environment and code switching. Can you think of positive aspects of&nbsp; employing code switching regularly? What about negative aspects?</span></p>\r\n'),(3,144,'Activity 4','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><em>In Botanic studies, rhizome is the main stem of the plant. It is the part of plant responsible for allowing the roots to grow and spread.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/rizoma.jpg\" style=\"height:300px; width:297px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><em>We can understand family as a rhizome. It is the part of our life that allow us to grow; and that the reason why we say that all members of our family are part of our family tree.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><em>When Helena and Caetano introduced us to their family, we could see how extensive it is. Watch the video again and combine the names of the people in the story and their family relationship with each other..</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Eron</em><em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</em><em>Julia</em><em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</em><em>Pilar</em><em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</em><em>Helena&nbsp; Caetano</em><em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Ex.: Helena = Caetano&rsquo;s sister</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Julia and Eron&rsquo;s daughter</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>PIlar&rsquo;s sister</em></p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n'),(3,147,'Video lesson on phonetics and English phonology','<p>Video lesson</p>\r\n'),(3,152,'Activity 1','<p><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">In the animation</span><em> Art for Thought</em><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">, the characters talk about the art exhibits they saw. They give their opinions and describe their feelings. In the snippet below, we underlined the expressions that express their feelings and opinions and made bold the adjectives and adverbs they used:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Nadine: _ So, what are your thoughts on the exbhibitions we&acute;ve just seen?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Daniel: _ </span><u><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">I was particularly </span><strong>impressed</strong></u><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\"> by the collages of parts of the body and poems.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Rosa: _ How come?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Daniel: _ </span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">They were somehow </span><strong>disconcerting</strong><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\"> to me</span></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. The words of the poems and the quotes resignified those sad, morbid organs into something else, but after reading the stories of the patients, I gained a whole new perspective.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Ben&iacute;cio: _ <u>Yeah, </u></span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">that was </span><strong>very</strong><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\"> </span><strong>impressive</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. </span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">This visit was </span><strong>interesting and thought-provoking</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. It was a great break from our readings and discussions.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Rosa: _ For sure. <u>The second exhibit made it feel like </u>recess time to me. </span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">All the pieces</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">were </span><strong>absolutely beautiful</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Nadine: _</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">I think that&rsquo;s exactly </span></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">what art can do to us: to give us a break, to inspire, to</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">unsettle, to shake us and make us feel alive. It opens up room for new thoughts</span><br />\r\n<span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">and understandings.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Ben&iacute;cio: _</span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">I felt more </span><strong>emotional</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\"> when I saw the video installations.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Daniel: _ Yes, </span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">they were </span><strong>very touching</strong></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Nadine: _ </span><strong>I loved the paintings</strong><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. Those colors </span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">really had an impact on me</span></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">. It was like they could move and invade my soul.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Rosa: _ Yes, those large pieces </span><u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">make us feel like</span></u><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\"> we are </span><em>in</em><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\"> the paintings.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">The underlined and bolded words in the snippet can be organized as:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/quadro%20unit%207.JPG\" style=\"height:286px; width:648px\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other examples of verbs to express feelings</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Pleasant feelings: like, enjoy, appreciate</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Unpleasant feelings: dislike, hate, fear</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other adjectives to talk about art:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Pleasant and positive feelings: Calm, cheerful, content, energetic, exciting, happy, joyful, peaceful,relaxed, stimulating, thought-provoking, tranquil</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent\">Unpleasant feelings: aggressive, angry, bored/boring, chilling, dark, depressing/depressed, distressing, dull, frightening, gloomy, insipid, lifeless,&nbsp; miserable, sad, somber, tearful, violent, unhappy&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other examples of expressions to talk about art:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">The work is really something to behold.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It is full of meaning and emotion.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It is the portrayal of a real-life observation.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It demonstrates the emotion of the artist.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It immersed me in a reflective journey.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">The work is of exceptional beauty.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It inspired me.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">It transforms the visible world.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Now let&acute;s practice giving opinions, defending our ideas and describing our feelings. Read the questions and use the recording tool to record your answers. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">What is your opinion on these images? How do you feel when you look at them?</span></p>\r\n'),(3,153,'Atividade de relacionar itens das colunas','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">&ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women (2018 version)&rdquo; is a short animation that tells us about the daily routines of four female characters: Ana, Maria, Lucia and Stela, who portray situations that many real women experience in their lives. They are hardworking, dignified people who have to </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">put up with</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"> </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">sexism</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"> and oppression in forms that vary from minor offenses to sexual harassment and violence.&nbsp; </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\" style=\"margin-left:222.75pt;\">\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse:collapse; border:none\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p><strong>Quick notes:</strong></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Put up with</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> (/ˈpʊtˈʌp</span><a href=\"https://easypronunciation.com/\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">ˈwɪ&theta;/)</span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> = tolerate, endure</span></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Sexism </strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">(/ˈsekˌsizəm/)= prejudice, discrimination or stereotyping based on sexual identifications</span></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Harassment</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> (/həˈrasmənt,ˈherəsmənt/) = intimidation or aggressive behavior that demeans, humiliates or embarrasses a person</span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">But&nbsp; what can be considered harassment? How does it take place? Let us read this definition by the United Nations Entity for Gender Equality and the Empowerment of Women:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Text 1</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><strong>Prohibition of discrimination, harassment, including sexual harassment, and abuse of authority</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Discrimination, sexual harassment and harassment are defined in SG&#39;s bulletin</span><a href=\"http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&amp;DS=ST/SGB/2008/5&amp;Lang=E\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\"> </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">ST/SGB/2008/5</span></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Discrimination is any unfair treatment or arbitrary distinction based on a person&rsquo;s race, sex, religion, nationality, ethnic origin, sexual orientation, disability, age, language, social origin or other status. Discrimination may be an isolated event affecting one person or a group of persons similarly situated, or may manifest itself through harassment or abuse of authority.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Harassment is any improper and unwelcome conduct that might reasonably be expected or be perceived to cause offence or humiliation to another person. Harassment may take the form of words, gestures or actions which tend to annoy, alarm, abuse, demean, intimidate, belittle, humiliate or embarrass another or which create an intimidating, hostile or offensive work environment. Harassment normally implies a series of incidents. Disagreement on work performance or on other work-related issues is normally not considered harassment and is not dealt with under the provisions of this policy but in the context of performance management.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Sexual harassment is any unwelcome sexual advance, request for sexual favour, verbal or physical conduct or gesture of a sexual nature, or any other behaviour of a sexual nature that might reasonably be expected or be perceived to cause offence or humiliation to another, when such conduct interferes with work, is made a condition of employment or creates an intimidating, hostile or offensive work environment. While typically involving a pattern of behaviour, it can take the form of a single incident. Sexual harassment may occur between persons of the opposite or same sex. Both males and females can be either the victims or the offenders.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">Source: </span><a href=\"https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/fpsexualharassment.htm\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/fpsexualharassment.htm</span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">. Access: 07/07/2019.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Given this explanation on the terms&nbsp;</span><em>discrimination</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">,&nbsp;</span><em>harassment</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">, and&nbsp;</span><em>abuse</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">, let&acute;s review some moments in the narrative of &ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women (2018)&rdquo; that portray situations what we consider to be cases of harassment; sexual harassent, and abuse. Which vocabulary in the left column do you consider express the situations portrayed in the scenes on the right column?</span></p>\r\n'),(3,155,'Activity 2','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Watch the animation</span><em> Art for thought</em><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\"> again. Listen, pause and repeat their dialogue.</span></span></p>\r\n'),(3,158,'Atividade 3 : Exercício de resposta dissertativa','<p>Now, it is your turn. Describe the day of a woman that you know (your mother, a friend, your sister, or you can describe your own day) using 5 different verbs. You can use the verbs suggested in the list.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>[ wake up - go - drive - take - be - work - study - teach - have - love - play - do - sleep]</em></p>\r\n'),(3,159,'Atividade 2: Complete the blanks','<p>The box below brings back the narrator ́s text in the animation &ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women&rdquo;. Complete the blanks with the verbs in parentheses in their appropriate conjugation.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:633px\">\r\n			<p><strong><u>Ana</u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>It&rsquo;s morning. We ______(see) Ana, our first character, preparing to go to work. She chooses a piece of clothing. But then, she ______ (notice) she may need to dress in more formal attire. She ______ (get) to work on time, and she ______ (work) hard, as always. She is one of the computer programmer chiefs in a big company. She assigns, coordinates, and reviews the work of her programming team. She has to analyze each product demand, suggest creative ways to develop it, and make the final decisions for the most efficient solutions. Attending meetings with her boss is one of her usual activities. Ana ______ (be) one of the very few women to be in a leadership position in the area of IT. Not only do men tend to rephrase her ideas, they also avoid give her credit for them. And they ______ (try) to oppress her by diverging the attention to stereotypical matters.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong><u>Maria</u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Our next strong female character is Maria. She is a single parent. She was abandoned by her violent partner, and she ______(raise) her daughter Matilda alone. They ______ (wake) up early so Maria can leave Matilda at day care before going to work. After leaving Matilda at daycare, Maria ______ (take) the bus to go to work. She ______(work) full time as a security guard. Maria is very vigilant and concerned with protecting women from abuse. After picking up Matilda, Maria still has some chores to do: she has to do her grocery shopping, clean the house, and after playing with Matilda, put her to bed. The most frightful thing is when Maria ______ (fall) asleep, but has nightmares with her ex-partner, who used to beat her.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong><u>Lucia</u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Among our hardworking, strong female characters, we have Lucia. She is editor-in-chief of a major book publisher. She works full time in the same building Ana and Maria ______ (work). Lucia is over her 40s now. She is single and very committed to work. She has a brilliant career in a job she ______ (love), but she is usually expected to fulfill a certain representation of women in a patriarchal model of society. Besides spending time with her parents sometimes, Lucia has an intense social and professional life. And sometimes she freely just ______ (choose) to be by herself.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong><u>Stela</u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Our last female character in this story is Stela. Stela is 16 years old. She is a great, passionate violin player. She ______ (practice) every day after school. As every woman, she has to put up with very offensive harassment and attempts to make her invisible and explored. When she ______ (play) the violin though, she ______ (find) her own, peaceful and safe place.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(3,160,'Activity 3','<p><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">Repeat the phrases you hear. Make sure to reproduce the intonation you hear and the facial expressions of the actors in the videos:</span></p>\r\n'),(3,161,'Atividade 4: Expressing emotions','<p>Complete the sentences with the correct adjective:</p>\r\n'),(3,162,'Practice of pronunciation of vowel phonemes 2','<p>In this activity, we will continue to practice the repetition of vowel phonemes. Shall we?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:14.6667px\">/u:/ root</span><span style=\"font-size:14.6667px\">​&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ʊ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ cook&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɔ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ caught&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɜ:</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ urban&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ə</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ annoy&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">ʌ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/ hut</span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n'),(3,163,'Atividade 5: Resposta dissertativa oral','<p>In what other situations do you feel&hellip; (mention at least one situation).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Example: I feel happy when I go to a wedding.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type:lower-alpha\">\r\n	<li>happy?</li>\r\n	<li>frightened?</li>\r\n	<li>angry?</li>\r\n	<li>disgusted?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n'),(3,166,'Atividade 6: Resposta dissertativa','<p>What emojis can we use to describe the emotions expressed in the previous exercise (happy, disgusted, frightened, and angry)? Select at least two emojis for each emotion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/atv6_1.png\" style=\"height:121px; width:648px\" /></strong></p>\r\n'),(3,167,'Pronunciation practice: consonant phonemes 1','<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">According to Dinah Callou &amp; Yonne Leite (1993), while phonetics studies the sounds as isolated physical-articulatory entities, phonology studies the sounds from a functional point of view, as elements integrating a linguistic system. Phonetics aims at describing the sounds and analyze their articulatory, acoustic and perceptive particularities. Meanwhile, phonology studies intentional phonological differences, which can be associated with differences in meaning. These two disciplines are seen as interdependent, once for phonological studies, one must take into consideration the phonetic, acoustic and/or articulatory aspects, in order to determine the distinctive units (phonemes) in a given language.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">As the phoneme is the smallest sound unit in a language that is capable of conveying a distinct meaning, in this activity you are going to practice all 44 phonemes that were mapped out in the English language.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">First, let&rsquo;s focus on the </span><strong>consonantal</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\"> phonemes. A consonant is a sound where there is obstruction or blocking of the airflow during its passage from your lungs through the vocal apparatus.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">On each video, you are going to listen to a word where the different consonant sounds are produced, and in the subtitles you will see the highlighted phoneme and the complete word.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Notice that the phonemes are symbols that come between bars / /. Most of the symbols used to represent the sounds are the same as the letters used in the Latin alphabet, but there are other symbols too, and each symbol is assigned to one specific sound.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Play the video, listen to the word and the phoneme pronunciation, then record your own voice and send it for feedback.</span></p>\r\n'),(3,168,'Pronunciation practice: consonant phonemes 2','<p>In this activity, we continue to exercise the pronunciation of consonant phonemes. Our focus now is on the phonemes and exemplar words:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54.0pt\"><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; /f/ for&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /v/ vibrant&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /&theta;/ thick&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /&eth;/ the</p>\r\n'),(3,171,'teste inglês','<p>descri&ccedil;&atilde;o</p>\r\n'),(3,172,'Activity 5','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">People leave their countries for many different reasons, like Eron did. Some of them move to another country looking for a better life, with better job opportunities and better chances to thrive. Others will move to a different country in order to survive, running away from war, conflicts and disasters. Match the columns with the best definitions for the words related to different types of people who migrate to another country.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12px\">&nbsp;Source: https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-46747502</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(3,173,'Activity 6','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Now that you matched the definitions, answer the questions below by recording audios for every question.</span></p>\r\n'),(3,174,'Activity 7 - Match the columns','<p>Match the idiomatic expression with its meaning.</p>\r\n'),(3,178,'Activity 7','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Match the country and with the correspondent nationality.</span></p>\r\n'),(3,179,'Activity 5: Voice Emotion Analysis ','<p>Voice Emotion Analysis</p>\r\n'),(3,180,'Activity 7: ','<p>There are other forms of expressing emotions in our writing too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What would it be the appropriate answer to express emotions in the following situations? More than one answer is possible.</p>\r\n'),(3,182,'Activity 8 - Modal Verbs Practice','<p>Check the best sense for these modal verbs.</p>\r\n'),(3,183,'Relacionar colunas inglês','<p>teste</p>\r\n'),(3,184,'Columns','<p>Match the columns using the idiomatic expressions</p>\r\n'),(3,185,'Activity 7','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Match the country and with the correspondent nationality.</span></p>\r\n'),(3,186,'testando','<p>testando</p>\r\n'),(3,187,'mult esc','<p>mult esc</p>\r\n'),(3,188,'Activity 8','<p>We can identify the phenomenon called gaslighting in the following situations. Read the dialogues and explain how this phenomenon works. What does the person do or say that can be considered an indication of gaslighting? In which part of the conversation is it more clear?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Situation 1:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:633px\">\r\n			<p>Sara works in a company in which there are periodic performance evaluations, with bonus for the best placed professionals. Sara found out that a colleague who held a similar position was making more money and working fewer hours. She decides to talk to her boss.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Mr. Fernandez, I&#39;d like to talk to you about the evaluations. I wonder if I am earning the same amount as Joaquim.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Sara, we know very well that your colleague is competent. This is the reason why you two may have different bonus.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Well, I know he is skilled. However, we have the same position, and I truly believe that I am entitled to get the same bonus as him.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Actually, he&#39;s been more competent than you.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Mr. Fernandez, according to the evaluations, my score is higher than his.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&ldquo;Are you sure? Have you checked the reports correctly?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Yes, I&rsquo;m sure.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;I&#39;m afraid you are being a bit unprofessional. Your colleague has more experience than you and he deserves his bonus. <strong>May I give you some advice, Sara? I really care about your career in this company, so beware of your ambition. There is no point in comparing your bonus to your other colleagues. This is not something that we see with good eyes here</strong>.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Situation 2:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:633px\">\r\n			<p>Luiza and Carlos are students in the Biotechnology undergraduate course.&nbsp; They are in the same group and they have to hand in a report to their professor by the end of the week. Luiza has been working in the report for over a week, and Carlos hasn&#39;t done much and hasn&#39;t returned her calls.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The deadline is getting closer and Luiza decides to talk to him about it. She sends him a message:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/8-1.png\" style=\"height:530px; width:269px\" /><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/8-2.png\" style=\"height:532px; width:335px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/8-3.png\" style=\"height:352px; width:292px\" /></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><u>(</u><a href=\"http://www.fakewhats.com/generator\">http://www.fakewhats.com/generator</a><u>) </u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Situation 3:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:633px\">\r\n			<p>Roberta and Jose are speakers in an international conference about Education Health. Each one is going to deliver a lecture in the auditorium. According to the program, Roberta was the first speaker, and Jose was next. However, Jose arrives in the auditorium and starts setting his presentation and slides. Roberta decides to talk to him politely:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Hi! I&#39;m sorry to interrupt you. My name is Roberta, and I am the first speaker. I&#39;m afraid I&#39;ll have to use the computer to organize my presentation.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Oh, nice to meet you Roberta! I&#39;m Jose. Hm... about that. I&#39;m sorry, but I have to go first.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Oh, why is that?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>&ldquo;Haven&#39;t anyone told you?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;No... in fact they haven&#39;t. I received an email confirmation from the organizers and the program hasn&#39;t changed. This is weird. What is wrong?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Well, but I&#39;m sure you don&#39;t mind, right? I mean... the order isn&#39;t a big deal.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;I really would like to keep the order. My flight is at 5pm, so I won&#39;t have enough time to get to the airport.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Oh, don&#39;t worry. Is this the only reason?The airport is near here. This is not a problem. Let&#39;s not make a storm in a teacup. &rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;I&#39;m not ma&hellip;&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;You know, the organizers have so many things to do during the conference. Are you sure you want to bother them with that? I would really appreciate if you could help me&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Then, Carla, who is part of the organization, approaches them: &ldquo;Roberta and Jose, is everything ok? Do you need any help?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Oh, everything is fine! I&#39;m just talking to my friend Roberta. I think she is in those days, if you know what I mean! hahaha&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Carla, has the order of presentations changed?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Hm... I don&#39;t think so. Why?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&ldquo;I&#39;m trying to tell Jose that I am the first speaker.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&quot;Well, I can&#39;t believe you still want to go first, Roberta. That is why is so difficult to deal with women, especially those who believe they are superior. They can&rsquo;t negotiate and are often selfish.&quot;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(3,189,'Activity 9','<p>Considering this definition, take a look at the cartoon and write True (T) or False (F) according to the statements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/9.jpg\" style=\"height:425px; width:358px\" /></p>\r\n'),(3,190,'Activity 10','<p>Quest&atilde;o aberta</p>\r\n'),(3,191,'Activity 9: True or False','<p>Considering this definition, take a look at the cartoon and write True (T) or False (F) according to the statements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/9.jpg\" style=\"height:425px; opacity:0.9; width:358px\" /></p>\r\n'),(3,192,'Activity 4: Different formulations','<p><em>What other formulations could we say to complete the speech balloons and maintain the friendly tone of the characters&#39; original conversations? For each blank, choose one of the 03 options proposed and speak into your microphone for feedback. Sometimes more than one option is correct.</em></p>\r\n'),(3,193,'Pronunciation practice: consonant phonemes 3','<p>In this activity, we continue to exercise the pronunciation of consonant phonemes. Our focus now is on the phonemes and exemplar words:</p>\r\n'),(3,194,'Pronunciation practice: consonant phonemes 4',''),(3,195,'Pronunciation practice: consonant phonemes 5',''),(3,196,'Pronunciation practice: consonant phonemes 6',''),(3,197,'Activity 7','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Match the country and with the correspondent nationality.</span></p>\r\n'),(3,198,'Activity 7','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Match the country and with the correspondent nationality.</span></p>\r\n'),(3,199,'Activity 4','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">Theme 2, in this lab, entitled &quot;</span>Academic Encounters&quot;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">,</span> <span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">explores some expressions and intonations that are possible in academic situations to agree or disagree with propositions or ask for clarifications, for example, and it also addresses the issue of social identifications and the exercise of power in and by language. Our characters in theme 7, &quot;</span>Art for Thought&quot;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial\">, are also in an academic situation: they are members of a research group and are discussing the relationship between art, language and the production of meanings. As they argue, they express their opinions, state opinions, among others. Shall we? Use the numbers in Column 1 to classify the phrases in column 2.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n'),(3,200,'Practice of pronunciation of vowel phonemes 3','<p>In this activity, we will continue to practice the repetition of vowel phonemes. Shall we?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">ɝ</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-size:11pt\">/ bird&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:transparent; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">/</span><span style=\"font-family:arial; 